Statement: Assignment3+4 was completed by Ling Leng and Jiali Yang, of which Assignment4 was completed by Ling Leng, and Assignment3 was completed by Jiali Yang

Economic Indicators and Migration Flows in New Zealand: Interactions and Policy Implications¶

Student name:Ling Leng¶

Student ID: 24014297¶

Introduction¶

This analysis analyzed New Zealand's economic and migration fields through the steps of importing datasets, data cleaning, EDA, and data visualization. In the context of globalization, New Zealand as an economy has received widespread attention for its immigration policies and economic strategies. This analysis aims to explore the relationship between New Zealand's GDP, government debt, inflation, unemployment and international migration flows to reveal how these economic indicators interact and influence migration trends. Through detailed data research, we hope to provide insights for policy making and help optimize the country's economic and immigration policies.

Dataset sources: Web scraping/States NZ¶

Research Questions¶

  1. What is the relationship between GDP per capita growth and government debt? How does government debt change during periods of good economic performance?
  2. How does inflation affect the inflow and outflow of immigrants? Does the relationship between inflation and unemployment conform to traditional economic theory?
  3. How do changes in government debt affect the net inflow of immigrants? What are the characteristics of migration flows during periods of high debt levels?
  4. How do immigration flows reflect changing economic conditions? At different stages of economic performance, in what ways is the impact of immigration on the economy reflected?

Executive Summary¶

[Some Basic Settings]
[Data Acquisition]: Web Scraping--Data Transform--Import static datasets--Data Transform
[Data Wrangling]: Data Clean--EDA/Data Visulisation

[Conclusion]

line-height: 1.2em; padding: .1em 0; line-height:1.25em;padding:0.2em;"> <span class="nowrap">Main data source:</span> <span class="nowrap"><b><a class="external text" href="https://www.cia.gov/the-world-factbook/countries/new-zealand" rel="nofollow"><i>CIA World Fact Book</i></a></b></span> <br/><i>All values, unless otherwise stated, are in <a href="/wiki/United_States_dollar" title="United States dollar">US dollars</a>.</i> </div></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>The <b>economy of New Zealand</b> is a <a href="/wiki/Developed_country" title="Developed country">highly developed</a> <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Free-market_economy" title="Free-market economy">free-market economy</a>.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-23"><a href="#cite_note-23">[23]</a></sup> It is the <a href="/wiki/List_of_countries_by_GDP_(nominal)" title="List of countries by GDP (nominal)">52nd</a>-largest national economy in the world when measured by <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Nominal_gross_domestic_product" title="Nominal gross domestic product">nominal gross domestic product</a> (GDP) and the <a href="/wiki/List_of_countries_by_GDP_(PPP)" title="List of countries by GDP (PPP)">62nd</a>-largest in the world when measured by <a href="/wiki/Purchasing_power_parity" title="Purchasing power parity">purchasing power parity</a> (PPP). New Zealand has one of the most <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Globalised" title="Globalised">globalised</a> economies and depends greatly on international trade, mainly with China, Australia, the <a href="/wiki/European_Union" title="European Union">European Union</a>, the United States, and Japan. New Zealand's 1983 <a href="/wiki/Closer_Economic_Relations" title="Closer Economic Relations">Closer Economic Relations</a> agreement with Australia means that the economy aligns closely with <a href="/wiki/Economy_of_Australia" title="Economy of Australia">that of Australia</a>. Among <a href="/wiki/OECD" title="OECD">OECD</a> nations, New Zealand has a highly efficient and strong <a href="/wiki/Welfare_in_New_Zealand" title="Welfare in New Zealand">social security system</a>; social expenditure stood at <a href="/wiki/Welfare_state#Effects" title="Welfare state">roughly 21.5% of GDP</a>.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Kenworthy_24-0"><a href="#cite_note-Kenworthy-24">[24]</a></sup><sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Bradley_et_al._25-0"><a href="#cite_note-Bradley_et_al.-25">[25]</a></sup><sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-26"><a href="#cite_note-26">[26]</a></sup>
</p>
<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a class="mw-file-description" href="/wiki/File:Nz_economy.png"><img class="mw-file-element" data-file-height="502" data-file-width="1403" decoding="async" height="79" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ed/Nz_economy.png/220px-Nz_economy.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ed/Nz_economy.png/330px-Nz_economy.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ed/Nz_economy.png/440px-Nz_economy.png 2x" width="220"/></a><figcaption>Economy of Aotearoa New Zealand by sector and organisation type</figcaption></figure><p>New Zealand's diverse economy is made up of various types of informal and formal organisations, divided between two sectors, <a href="/wiki/Public_sector" title="Public sector">public</a> and <a href="/wiki/Private_sector" title="Private sector">private</a>. It has a sizeable <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Service_sector" title="Service sector">service sector</a>, accounting for 63% of all GDP activity as of 2013<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup>.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-profile_economy_27-0"><a href="#cite_note-profile_economy-27">[27]</a></sup> As a large island nation New Zealand has abundant natural resources and mineral wealth.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-28"><a href="#cite_note-28">[28]</a></sup> Prominent manufacturing industries include aluminium production, food processing, metal fabrication, wood and paper products. Mining, manufacturing, electricity, gas, water, and waste services accounted for 16.5% of GDP as of 2013<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup>.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-profile_economy_27-1"><a href="#cite_note-profile_economy-27">[27]</a></sup> The primary sector continues to dominate New Zealand's exports, despite accounting for only 6.5% of GDP as of 2013<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup>.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-profile_economy_27-2"><a href="#cite_note-profile_economy-27">[27]</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/Information_technology_industry_in_New_Zealand" title="Information technology industry in New Zealand">information technology sector</a> is growing rapidly.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-29"><a href="#cite_note-29">[29]</a></sup>
</p><p>The major capital market is the <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/New_Zealand_Exchange" title="New Zealand Exchange">New Zealand Exchange</a> (NZX). As of February 2023<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup>, NZX had a total of 338 listed securities, equity, debt and funds with a combined market capitalisation of NZD $226 billion.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-30"><a href="#cite_note-30">[30]</a></sup> New Zealand's currency, the <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand_dollar" title="New Zealand dollar">New Zealand dollar</a> (informally known as the "Kiwi dollar"), also circulates in four Pacific Island territories. The New Zealand dollar is the 10th-most traded currency in the world.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-BIS_31-0"><a href="#cite_note-BIS-31">[31]</a></sup>
</p>
<style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r886046785">.mw-parser-output .toclimit-2 .toclevel-1 ul,.mw-parser-output .toclimit-3 .toclevel-2 ul,.mw-parser-output .toclimit-4 .toclevel-3 ul,.mw-parser-output .toclimit-5 .toclevel-4 ul,.mw-parser-output .toclimit-6 .toclevel-5 ul,.mw-parser-output .toclimit-7 .toclevel-6 ul{display:none}</style><div class="toclimit-4"><meta property="mw:PageProp/toc"/></div>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="History">History</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: History"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r1033289096">.mw-parser-output .hatnote{font-style:italic}.mw-parser-output div.hatnote{padding-left:1.6em;margin-bottom:0.5em}.mw-parser-output .hatnote i{font-style:normal}.mw-parser-output .hatnote+link+.hatnote{margin-top:-0.5em}</style><div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Economic_history_of_New_Zealand" title="Economic history of New Zealand">Economic history of New Zealand</a></div>
<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a class="mw-file-description" href="/wiki/File:Fonterra_Facility_Near_Hamilton.jpg"><img class="mw-file-element" data-file-height="1000" data-file-width="1800" decoding="async" height="122" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a9/Fonterra_Facility_Near_Hamilton.jpg/220px-Fonterra_Facility_Near_Hamilton.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a9/Fonterra_Facility_Near_Hamilton.jpg/330px-Fonterra_Facility_Near_Hamilton.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a9/Fonterra_Facility_Near_Hamilton.jpg/440px-Fonterra_Facility_Near_Hamilton.jpg 2x" width="220"/></a><figcaption>Agriculture (especially dairy farming – such as for the <a href="/wiki/Fonterra" title="Fonterra">Fonterra</a> plant shown) is a major export earner</figcaption></figure>
<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a class="mw-file-description" href="/wiki/File:Kinleith_Mill,_Tokoroa,_New_Zealand.jpg"><img class="mw-file-element" data-file-height="459" data-file-width="617" decoding="async" height="164" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/42/Kinleith_Mill%2C_Tokoroa%2C_New_Zealand.jpg/220px-Kinleith_Mill%2C_Tokoroa%2C_New_Zealand.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/42/Kinleith_Mill%2C_Tokoroa%2C_New_Zealand.jpg/330px-Kinleith_Mill%2C_Tokoroa%2C_New_Zealand.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/42/Kinleith_Mill%2C_Tokoroa%2C_New_Zealand.jpg/440px-Kinleith_Mill%2C_Tokoroa%2C_New_Zealand.jpg 2x" width="220"/></a><figcaption>An aerial view of the <a href="/wiki/Kinleith_Mill" title="Kinleith Mill">Kinleith Mill</a>. Forestry exports are an important component of New Zealand's economy.</figcaption></figure>
<p>For many years New Zealand's economy was built on a narrow range of agricultural products, such as wool, meat and dairy. These products became New Zealand's staple and most valuable exports, underpinning the success of the economy, from the 1850s until the 1970s.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Page_4_–_Early_pastoral_economy_32-0"><a href="#cite_note-Page_4_–_Early_pastoral_economy-32">[32]</a></sup> For example, from 1920 to the late 1930s, the dairy export quota was usually around 35% of New Zealand's total exports, and in some years made up almost 45%.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-NZHA_33-0"><a href="#cite_note-NZHA-33">[33]</a></sup> Due to the high demand for these primary products, manifested by the <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand_wool_boom" title="New Zealand wool boom">New Zealand wool boom</a> of 1951, New Zealand had one of the highest <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Standards_of_living" title="Standards of living">standards of living</a> in the world for 70 years.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-refridge1_34-0"><a href="#cite_note-refridge1-34">[34]</a></sup>
</p><p>In the 1960s, prices for these traditional exports declined, and in 1973 New Zealand lost its <a href="/wiki/Preferential_trading_area" title="Preferential trading area">preferential trading position</a> with the United Kingdom when the latter joined the <a href="/wiki/European_Economic_Community" title="European Economic Community">European Economic Community</a>. Partly as a result, from 1970 to 1990, the relative New Zealand GDP per capita <a href="/wiki/Purchasing_power_parity" title="Purchasing power parity">adjusted for purchasing power</a> declined from about 115% of the <a href="/wiki/OECD" title="OECD">OECD</a> average to 80%.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-35"><a href="#cite_note-35">[35]</a></sup>
</p><p>Between 1984 and 1993, New Zealand changed from a somewhat closed and centrally controlled economy to one of the most open economies in the OECD.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-36"><a href="#cite_note-36">[36]</a></sup> In a process often referred to in New Zealand as <a href="/wiki/Rogernomics" title="Rogernomics">Rogernomics</a>, successive governments introduced policies which dramatically liberalised the economy.
</p><p>In 2005, the <a href="/wiki/World_Bank" title="World Bank">World Bank</a> praised New Zealand as the most business-friendly country in the world.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-SALE_37-0"><a href="#cite_note-SALE-37">[37]</a></sup><sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-IHT_38-0"><a href="#cite_note-IHT-38">[38]</a></sup> The economy diversified and by 2008, tourism had become the single biggest generator of foreign exchange.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-diversify_39-0"><a href="#cite_note-diversify-39">[39]</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Early_years">Early years</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Early years"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Prior to European settlement and colonisation of New Zealand, <a href="/wiki/M%C4%81ori_people" title="Māori people">Māori</a> had a subsistence economy, the basic economic unit of which was the sub-tribe or <a href="/wiki/Hap%C5%AB" title="Hapū">hapū</a>.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-maori_economy_40-0"><a href="#cite_note-maori_economy-40">[40]</a></sup> From the 1790s, the waters around New Zealand were visited by British, French and American <a href="/wiki/Whaling_in_New_Zealand" title="Whaling in New Zealand">whaling</a>, <a href="/wiki/Seal_hunting" title="Seal hunting">sealing</a> and trading ships. Their crews traded European goods, including guns and metal tools, for Māori food, water, wood, <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/New_Zealand_flax" title="New Zealand flax">flax</a> and <a href="/wiki/Prostitution" title="Prostitution">sex</a>.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-king_41-0"><a href="#cite_note-king-41">[41]</a></sup> Their increasing lawlessness and plans for formal settlement by the <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand_Company" title="New Zealand Company">New Zealand Company</a> were two of the drivers behind the signing of the <a href="/wiki/Treaty_of_Waitangi" title="Treaty of Waitangi">Treaty of Waitangi</a> in 1840, which established New Zealand as a <a href="/wiki/Colony_of_New_Zealand" title="Colony of New Zealand">colony</a>. Settlers continued to be dependent on Māori for food until the 1860s.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-maori_economy_40-1"><a href="#cite_note-maori_economy-40">[40]</a></sup><sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-king_41-1"><a href="#cite_note-king-41">[41]</a></sup> From then immigrants became self-sufficient in farming, and started quarrying a variety of minerals including gold, which was discovered at Gabriel's Gully in <a href="/wiki/Central_Otago" title="Central Otago">Central Otago</a>, leading to the <a href="/wiki/Otago_Gold_Rush" title="Otago Gold Rush">Otago Gold Rush</a> in 1861. Settlements flourished in areas where these quarries were established. In the 1880s, Dunedin became the richest city in the country largely on the back of investments from the gold rush.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-42"><a href="#cite_note-42">[42]</a></sup>
</p><p>Sheep farming began in the <a href="/wiki/Wairarapa" title="Wairarapa">Wairarapa</a> but soon spread up and down the east coast from Southland to the East Cape once rudimentary roads and transport became available. Much of the land used for farming was taken or leased from Māori. Sheep numbers grew quickly and by the mid-1850s, there were already a million sheep in New Zealand; by the early 1870s, there were 10 million.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Page_4_–_Early_pastoral_economy_32-1"><a href="#cite_note-Page_4_–_Early_pastoral_economy-32">[32]</a></sup> Wool became the first staple export, initially exported from the Wellington settlement in the late 1850s, although unrefrigerated meat and dairy products were exported as far as Australia.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Page_4_–_Early_pastoral_economy_32-2"><a href="#cite_note-Page_4_–_Early_pastoral_economy-32">[32]</a></sup>
</p><p>In the 1870s, <a href="/wiki/Julius_Vogel" title="Julius Vogel">Julius Vogel</a> was periodically both colonial treasurer and premier. He viewed New Zealand as a "Britain of the South Seas"<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-43"><a href="#cite_note-43">[43]</a></sup> and began the development of infrastructure in New Zealand investing heavily in roads, railways, telegraphs and bridges funded by public borrowing.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-44"><a href="#cite_note-44">[44]</a></sup> Progress slowed after the collapse of the <a href="/wiki/City_of_Glasgow_Bank" title="City of Glasgow Bank">City of Glasgow Bank</a> in 1878 which led to a contraction in credit from London, the centre of the world's financial system at the time. Economic activity was depressed for some years afterwards, until refrigeration was introduced in 1882.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-refridge1_34-1"><a href="#cite_note-refridge1-34">[34]</a></sup> This enabled New Zealand to start exporting meat and other frozen products to the United Kingdom. Refrigeration transformed and shaped the development of the economy but, in the process, established New Zealand's economic dependence on Britain.
</p><p>The success of refrigeration was directly related to the growth and development of farming in the country. In the 19th century, the bulk of economic activity was in the <a href="/wiki/South_Island" title="South Island">South Island</a> of New Zealand. From around 1900, dairy farming became increasingly viable in areas which were less suitable for sheep, particularly in Northland, the Waikato and Taranaki. As dairying developed, the <a href="/wiki/North_Island" title="North Island">North Island</a> slowly became more important to the economy.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-refridge_45-0"><a href="#cite_note-refridge-45">[45]</a></sup> Britain led on to be the sole market for meat and animal products in New Zealand, owing to the increase in its land cultivation and farming. The dairy farming can therefore be seen as a response to the powerful market demands in Europe, transforming not only New Zealand's countryside, economy and production techniques, but also causing migration in order to create the needed supply of dairy farming.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-46"><a href="#cite_note-46">[46]</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="20th_century">20th century</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: 20th century"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Reserve_Bank_of_New_Zealand" title="Reserve Bank of New Zealand">Reserve Bank of New Zealand</a> was established as New Zealand's <a href="/wiki/Central_bank" title="Central bank">central bank</a> on 1 August 1934. Up until that time New Zealand's monetary policy had been set in the United Kingdom, and the <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/New_Zealand_Pound" title="New Zealand Pound">New Zealand Pound</a> was issued by private banks. A separate central bank gave New Zealand's government control of monetary policy for the first time,<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-central_bank_47-0"><a href="#cite_note-central_bank-47">[47]</a></sup> although New Zealand remained part of the <a href="/wiki/Sterling_area" title="Sterling area">sterling area</a> by pegging its pound to the British <a href="/wiki/Pound_sterling" title="Pound sterling">pound sterling</a> until the introduction of the <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand_dollar" title="New Zealand dollar">New Zealand dollar</a> in 1967, after which the dollar was instead pegged to the <a href="/wiki/United_States_dollar" title="United States dollar">United States dollar</a>.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-48"><a href="#cite_note-48">[48]</a></sup>
</p><p>By the mid-20th century, pastoral-farming products made up more than 90% of New Zealand's exports,<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-refridge_45-1"><a href="#cite_note-refridge-45">[45]</a></sup> 65% of which was going to Britain in the 1950s. Having a secure market with guaranteed prices also enabled New Zealand to impose high tariffs on imported goods from other countries. Tough import controls gave local manufacturers the ability to produce similar products locally, broaden the base of jobs available in New Zealand and still compete against higher priced imports.
</p><p>This prosperity continued up to 1955 at which point Britain stopped giving New Zealand guaranteed prices for its exports.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-New_Zealand's_trade_history_49-0"><a href="#cite_note-New_Zealand's_trade_history-49">[49]</a></sup> From then on, what New Zealand received was dictated by the free market. As a result, during the 1950s and 1960s the country's standard of living began to slip as the export sector was no longer able to pay for the level of imported goods required to meet the country's growing <a href="/wiki/Consumerism" title="Consumerism">consumerism</a>.
</p>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a class="mw-file-description" href="/wiki/File:Tiwai_Point_Aluminium_Smelter.jpg"><img class="mw-file-element" data-file-height="1200" data-file-width="1600" decoding="async" height="165" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/43/Tiwai_Point_Aluminium_Smelter.jpg/220px-Tiwai_Point_Aluminium_Smelter.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/43/Tiwai_Point_Aluminium_Smelter.jpg/330px-Tiwai_Point_Aluminium_Smelter.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/43/Tiwai_Point_Aluminium_Smelter.jpg/440px-Tiwai_Point_Aluminium_Smelter.jpg 2x" width="220"/></a><figcaption><a href="/wiki/Tiwai_Point_Aluminium_Smelter" title="Tiwai Point Aluminium Smelter">Tiwai Point Aluminium Smelter</a>, opened in 1971</figcaption></figure>
<p>Britain applied to join the <a href="/wiki/European_Economic_Community" title="European Economic Community">European Economic Community</a> (EEC) in 1961, but was vetoed by the French. The government of <a href="/wiki/Keith_Holyoake" title="Keith Holyoake">Keith Holyoake</a> reacted by attempting to diversify New Zealand's export markets, signing the first free trade agreement (<a href="/wiki/Closer_Economic_Relations" title="Closer Economic Relations">Australia New Zealand Free Trade Agreement</a>) in 1965,<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-50"><a href="#cite_note-50">[50]</a></sup> and opening new diplomatic posts in Hong Kong, Jakarta, Saigon, Los Angeles and San Francisco.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-NZHA_33-1"><a href="#cite_note-NZHA-33">[33]</a></sup> Britain applied again to join the EEC in 1967, and entered into negotiations for membership in 1970. Holyoake's deputy and successor, <a href="/wiki/Jack_Marshall" title="Jack Marshall">Jack Marshall</a>, (briefly Prime Minister in 1972) negotiated continued access for New Zealand exports to the United Kingdom under the so-called "Luxembourg Agreement".<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-luxembourg_51-0"><a href="#cite_note-luxembourg-51">[51]</a></sup>
</p><p>Britain gained full membership of the EEC on 1 January 1973, and all trade agreements with New Zealand came to an end, except the Luxembourg Agreement.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-luxembourg_51-1"><a href="#cite_note-luxembourg-51">[51]</a></sup> By the end of that year, only 26.8% of New Zealand's exports were to Britain.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-52"><a href="#cite_note-52">[52]</a></sup> This had a significant effect on the standard of living. In 1953, New Zealand had the third highest standard in the world. By 1978, it had dropped to 22nd place.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-New_Zealand's_trade_history_49-1"><a href="#cite_note-New_Zealand's_trade_history-49">[49]</a></sup>
</p><p>Having lost unrestricted access to its traditional market, New Zealand continued to search for alternative export markets and diversify its economy. The Government of <a href="/wiki/Norman_Kirk" title="Norman Kirk">Norman Kirk</a>, who succeeded Marshall, put greater emphasis on expanding New Zealand's trade, especially with South East Asia. Following the <a href="/wiki/Yom_Kippur_War" title="Yom Kippur War">Yom Kippur War</a> in October 1973, an oil embargo was put in place by the Middle Eastern oil exporters, leading to the <a href="/wiki/1973_oil_crisis" title="1973 oil crisis">1973 oil crisis</a>. This compounded New Zealand's dire economic situation further. Inflation greatly increased as the cost of transport and imported goods soared, causing standards of living to decline.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-inflation_53-0"><a href="#cite_note-inflation-53">[53]</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Think_Big">Think Big</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Think Big"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Think_Big" title="Think Big">Think Big</a></div>
<p>Following the <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/1979_energy_crisis" title="1979 energy crisis">1979 energy crisis</a> resulting from the <a href="/wiki/Iranian_Revolution" title="Iranian Revolution">Iranian Revolution</a> of that year, <a href="/wiki/Robert_Muldoon" title="Robert Muldoon">Robert Muldoon</a>, the prime minister between 1975 and 1984, instituted an economic strategy known as <a href="/wiki/Think_Big" title="Think Big">Think Big</a>. Large scale industrial plants were established based on New Zealand's abundant natural gas. A new range of products for export such as ammonia, urea fertilizer, methanol and petrol were produced and with greater use of electricity (with the electrification of the <a href="/wiki/North_Island_Main_Trunk" title="North Island Main Trunk">North Island Main Trunk</a> railway) with the goal that this would reduce New Zealand's dependence on oil imports.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-diversify_39-1"><a href="#cite_note-diversify-39">[39]</a></sup>
</p><p>Other projects included the <a href="/wiki/Clyde_Dam" title="Clyde Dam">Clyde Dam</a> on the <a href="/wiki/Clutha_River" title="Clutha River">Clutha River</a>, which was built to meet a growing demand for electricity, and the expansion of the <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand_Steel" title="New Zealand Steel">New Zealand Steel</a> plant at Glenbrook.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-In_the_shadow_of_Think_Big_54-0"><a href="#cite_note-In_the_shadow_of_Think_Big-54">[54]</a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/Tiwai_Point_Aluminium_Smelter" title="Tiwai Point Aluminium Smelter">Tiwai Point Aluminium Smelter</a>, which opened in 1971, was also upgraded as part of the Think Big strategy and now brings in approximately NZ$1 billion in exports every year.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-aluminium_exports_55-0"><a href="#cite_note-aluminium_exports-55">[55]</a></sup>
</p><p>Unfortunately for New Zealand, most of these projects only came on line at the same time as oil prices dropped during the <a href="/wiki/1980s_oil_glut" title="1980s oil glut">1980s oil glut</a>. The price of crude went from more than US$90 a barrel in 1980, to about US$30 a few years later. Because these Think Big projects required massive borrowing to get started, public debt soared from $4.2 billion in 1975 when Muldoon became prime minister to $21.9 billion when he left office nine years later. Inflation remained rampant, averaging 11% in the 1980s.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-inflation_53-1"><a href="#cite_note-inflation-53">[53]</a></sup> Once Labour came to power in 1984, many of these projects were sold to private industry as part of a wider sale of state-assets.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-In_the_shadow_of_Think_Big_54-1"><a href="#cite_note-In_the_shadow_of_Think_Big-54">[54]</a></sup>
</p><p>The Muldoon Government did make some moves towards deregulation however. For example, in 1982 it removed the <a href="/wiki/Transport_Licensing_Act_1931" title="Transport Licensing Act 1931">transport licensing restrictions</a> on road carriers carting goods more than 150 km, and turned <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand_Railways_Department" title="New Zealand Railways Department">the Railways Department</a> into a <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand_Railways_Corporation" title="New Zealand Railways Corporation">statutory corporation</a>.
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Rogernomics">Rogernomics</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Rogernomics"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Rogernomics" title="Rogernomics">Rogernomics</a></div>
<style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r1023981488">@media all and (max-width:720px){.mw-parser-output .rquote{width:auto!important;float:none!important}}</style><style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r1211633275">.mw-parser-output .templatequote{overflow:hidden;margin:1em 0;padding:0 32px}.mw-parser-output .templatequote .templatequotecite{line-height:1.5em;text-align:left;padding-left:1.6em;margin-top:0}</style><blockquote class="templatequote rquote" style="float: right; width: 33%;"><p>Between 1984 and 1993, New Zealand underwent radical economic reform, moving from what had probably been the most protected, regulated and state-dominated system of any capitalist democracy to an extreme position at the open, competitive, free-market end of the spectrum.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-56"><a href="#cite_note-56">[56]</a></sup></p></blockquote>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Fourth_Labour_Government_of_New_Zealand" title="Fourth Labour Government of New Zealand">Fourth Labour government</a>, elected in July 1984, moved away from government intervention in the economy and allowed <a href="/wiki/Free_market" title="Free market">free market</a> mechanisms to dominate. These reforms became known as "Rogernomics", named after minister of finance from 1984 to 1988, <a href="/wiki/Roger_Douglas" title="Roger Douglas">Roger Douglas</a>. The changes included making the Reserve Bank independent of political decisions; performance contracts for senior civil servants; public sector finance reform based on <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Accrual_accounting" title="Accrual accounting">accrual accounting</a>; tax neutrality; subsidy-free agriculture; and industry-neutral competition regulation. Government subsidies including <a href="/wiki/Agricultural_subsidy" title="Agricultural subsidy">agricultural subsidies</a> were eliminated; import regulations were loosened up; the exchange rate was floated; and controls on <a href="/wiki/Interest_rate" title="Interest rate">interest rates</a>, wages, and prices were removed; and personal rates of taxation were reduced. Tight monetary policy and major efforts to reduce the <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Government_budget_deficit" title="Government budget deficit">government budget deficit</a> brought the inflation rate down from an annual rate of more than 18% in 1987. The deregulation of government-owned enterprises in the 1980s and 1990s reduced government's role in the economy and permitted the retirement of some <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Public_debt" title="Public debt">public debt</a>.
</p>
<figure typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a class="mw-file-description" href="/wiki/File:New_Zealand_Dollar_-_Australian_Dollar_Exchange_Rate.webp"><img class="mw-file-element" data-file-height="479" data-file-width="1583" decoding="async" height="101" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f6/New_Zealand_Dollar_-_Australian_Dollar_Exchange_Rate.webp/335px-New_Zealand_Dollar_-_Australian_Dollar_Exchange_Rate.webp.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f6/New_Zealand_Dollar_-_Australian_Dollar_Exchange_Rate.webp/503px-New_Zealand_Dollar_-_Australian_Dollar_Exchange_Rate.webp.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f6/New_Zealand_Dollar_-_Australian_Dollar_Exchange_Rate.webp/670px-New_Zealand_Dollar_-_Australian_Dollar_Exchange_Rate.webp.png 2x" width="335"/></a><figcaption><style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r981673959">.mw-parser-output .legend{page-break-inside:avoid;break-inside:avoid-column}.mw-parser-output .legend-color{display:inline-block;min-width:1.25em;height:1.25em;line-height:1.25;margin:1px 0;text-align:center;border:1px solid black;background-color:transparent;color:black}.mw-parser-output .legend-text{}</style><div class="legend"><span class="legend-color mw-no-invert" style="border: 1px solid #C8102E;background-color:#012169; color:white;"> </span> <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand_dollar" title="New Zealand dollar">New Zealand Dollar</a> / <a href="/wiki/Australian_dollar" title="Australian dollar">Australian Dollar</a> <a href="/wiki/Exchange_rate" title="Exchange rate">exchange rate</a></div></figcaption></figure>
<figure typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a class="mw-file-description" href="/wiki/File:New_Zealand_Dollar_-_USD_Exchange_Rate.webp"><img class="mw-file-element" data-file-height="407" data-file-width="1536" decoding="async" height="79" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3a/New_Zealand_Dollar_-_USD_Exchange_Rate.webp/300px-New_Zealand_Dollar_-_USD_Exchange_Rate.webp.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3a/New_Zealand_Dollar_-_USD_Exchange_Rate.webp/450px-New_Zealand_Dollar_-_USD_Exchange_Rate.webp.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3a/New_Zealand_Dollar_-_USD_Exchange_Rate.webp/600px-New_Zealand_Dollar_-_USD_Exchange_Rate.webp.png 2x" width="300"/></a><figcaption><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r981673959" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><div class="legend"><span class="legend-color mw-no-invert" style="border: 1px solid #C8102E;background-color:#012169; color:white;"> </span> <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand_dollar" title="New Zealand dollar">NZD</a> / <a href="/wiki/United_States_dollar" title="United States dollar">USD</a> <a href="/wiki/Exchange_rate" title="Exchange rate">exchange rate</a></div></figcaption></figure>
<p>The new Government was faced with an exchange rate crisis the day after it was elected. Speculators expected the change of government to result in a 20% devaluation of the <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand_dollar" title="New Zealand dollar">New Zealand dollar</a>, which led to the <a href="/wiki/1984_New_Zealand_constitutional_crisis" title="1984 New Zealand constitutional crisis">1984 New Zealand constitutional crisis</a> due to Muldoon's refusal to devalue, worsening the currency crisis further. As a result, the dollar was <a href="/wiki/Floating_exchange_rate" title="Floating exchange rate">floated</a> on 4 March 1985, allowing for the value of the dollar to change with the market.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-exchangerate_57-0"><a href="#cite_note-exchangerate-57">[57]</a></sup> Prior to the dollar being floated, the dollar was <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Fixed_exchange-rate_system" title="Fixed exchange-rate system">pegged</a> against a basket of currencies.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-exchangerate_57-1"><a href="#cite_note-exchangerate-57">[57]</a></sup>
</p><p>Financial markets were deregulated and tariffs on imported goods lowered and phased out. At the same time subsidies to many industries, notably agriculture, were removed or significantly reduced. Income and company taxes were reduced and the top <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Marginal_tax_rate" title="Marginal tax rate">marginal tax rate</a> was reduced from 66% to 33%. These were replaced by a comprehensive tax on goods and services (<a href="/wiki/Goods_and_Services_Tax_(New_Zealand)" title="Goods and Services Tax (New Zealand)">GST</a>) initially set at 10%, then increased to 12.5% in 1989 and to 15% in 2010. A <a href="/wiki/Surtax" title="Surtax">surtax</a> on universal superannuation was also introduced.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-king_41-2"><a href="#cite_note-king-41">[41]</a></sup> Many government departments were corporatised, and from 1 April 1987 became <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/State-owned_enterprises_of_New_Zealand" title="State-owned enterprises of New Zealand">State owned enterprises</a>, required to make a profit. The new corporations shed thousands of jobs adding to unemployment; Electricity Corporation 3,000; Coal Corporation 4,000; Forestry Corporation 5,000; New Zealand Post 8,000.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTERussell1996119_58-0"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTERussell1996119-58">[58]</a></sup>
</p><p>The wage and price freeze of the early eighties coupled with the removal of financial restrictions and a lack of investment opportunities, led to a speculative bubble on New Zealand's sharemarket, <a href="/wiki/Black_Monday_(1987)" title="Black Monday (1987)">sharemarket crash of 1987</a>, in which New Zealand's sharemarket shed 60% from its 1987 peak, and taking several years to recover.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-NZSE_59-0"><a href="#cite_note-NZSE-59">[59]</a></sup><sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-60"><a href="#cite_note-60">[60]</a></sup>
</p>
<figure typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a class="mw-file-description" href="/wiki/File:New_Zealand_money_supply_and_inflation.webp"><img class="mw-file-element" data-file-height="437" data-file-width="1571" decoding="async" height="81" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5f/New_Zealand_money_supply_and_inflation.webp/290px-New_Zealand_money_supply_and_inflation.webp.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5f/New_Zealand_money_supply_and_inflation.webp/435px-New_Zealand_money_supply_and_inflation.webp.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5f/New_Zealand_money_supply_and_inflation.webp/580px-New_Zealand_money_supply_and_inflation.webp.png 2x" width="290"/></a><figcaption>New Zealand money supply and inflation <link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r981673959" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><div class="legend"><span class="legend-line mw-no-invert" style="display: inline-block; vertical-align: middle; width: 1.67em; height: 0; border-style: none; border-top: 2px dotted black;border-top:#C8102E solid 3px;"> </span> M3 money supply increases</div> <link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r981673959" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><div class="legend"><span class="legend-line mw-no-invert" style="display: inline-block; vertical-align: middle; width: 1.67em; height: 0; border-style: none; border-top: 2px dotted black;border-top:#61D836 solid 3px;"> </span> Housing inflation</div> <link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r981673959" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><div class="legend"><span class="legend-line mw-no-invert" style="display: inline-block; vertical-align: middle; width: 1.67em; height: 0; border-style: none; border-top: 2px dotted black;border-top:#00A2FF solid 3px;"> </span> <a href="/wiki/Consumer_price_index" title="Consumer price index">Consumer price index</a></div></figcaption></figure>
<p>Inflation continued to be a major problem afflicting the New Zealand economy. Between 1985 and 1992, inflation averaged 9% per year and the economy was in recession.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Kelsey,_Jane_61-0"><a href="#cite_note-Kelsey,_Jane-61">[61]</a></sup> The unemployment rate rose from 3.6% to 11%,<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-62"><a href="#cite_note-62">[62]</a></sup> New Zealand's credit rating dropped twice, and foreign debt quadrupled.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Kelsey,_Jane_61-1"><a href="#cite_note-Kelsey,_Jane-61">[61]</a></sup> In 1989 the <a href="/wiki/Reserve_Bank_of_New_Zealand" title="Reserve Bank of New Zealand">Reserve Bank Act 1989</a> was passed, creating strict <a href="/wiki/Monetary_policy" title="Monetary policy">monetary policy</a> under the sole control of the Reserve Bank Governor. From then on the Reserve Bank focused on keeping inflation low and stable, using the <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Official_Cash_Rate" title="Official Cash Rate">Official Cash Rate</a> (OCR) – the price of borrowing money in New Zealand – as its primary means to do so. As a result, inflation rates fell to an average of 2.5% in the 1990s, compared to 12% in the 1970s.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-inflation_53-2"><a href="#cite_note-inflation-53">[53]</a></sup> However, the tightening of monetary policy contributed to rising unemployment in the early 1990s.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-63"><a href="#cite_note-63">[63]</a></sup>
</p><p>The Labour Party was greatly divided over Rogernomics, especially following the 1987 sharemarket crash and its effect on the economy, which slumped along with the rest of the world into <a href="/wiki/Early_1990s_recession" title="Early 1990s recession">recession in the early 1990s</a>. The National Party was returned to power at the <a href="/wiki/1990_New_Zealand_general_election" title="1990 New Zealand general election">1990 general election</a> and <a href="/wiki/Ruth_Richardson" title="Ruth Richardson">Ruth Richardson</a> became minister of finance under Prime Minister Jim Bolger. The new Government was again thrown a major economic challenge, with the then state-owned <a href="/wiki/Bank_of_New_Zealand" title="Bank of New Zealand">Bank of New Zealand</a> needing a bail-out to stay operational.
</p><p>Richardson's first budget in 1991, nicknamed the '<a href="/wiki/Mother_of_all_Budgets" title="Mother of all Budgets">Mother of all Budgets</a>',<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ReferenceB_64-0"><a href="#cite_note-ReferenceB-64">[64]</a></sup> attempted to address constant fiscal deficits and borrowing by cutting state spending. Unemployment and social welfare benefits were cut and 'market rents' were introduced for state houses – in some cases tripling the rents of low-income people.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-65"><a href="#cite_note-65">[65]</a></sup> Richardson also introduced <a href="/wiki/User_pays" title="User pays">user-pays</a> requirements in hospitals and schools.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ReferenceB_64-1"><a href="#cite_note-ReferenceB-64">[64]</a></sup> These reforms became known derisively as <a href="/wiki/Ruthanasia" title="Ruthanasia">Ruthanasia</a>.
</p><p>By this time, New Zealand's economy faced serious social problems; the number of New Zealanders estimated to be living in poverty grew by at least 35% between 1989 and 1992;<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Kelsey,_Jane_61-2"><a href="#cite_note-Kelsey,_Jane-61">[61]</a></sup> many of the promised economic benefits of the experiment never materialised.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-66"><a href="#cite_note-66">[66]</a></sup> Gross domestic product per capita stagnated between 1986–87 and 1993–94, and by March 1992 unemployment rose to 11.1%<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-67"><a href="#cite_note-67">[67]</a></sup> Between 1985 and 1992, New Zealand's economy grew by 4.7% during the same period in which the average <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Organisation_for_Economic_Co-operation_and_Development" title="Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development">OECD</a> nation grew by 28.2%.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-68"><a href="#cite_note-68">[68]</a></sup> From 1984 to 1993 inflation averaged 9% per year, New Zealand's credit rating dropped twice, and foreign debt quadrupled.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Kelsey,_Jane_61-3"><a href="#cite_note-Kelsey,_Jane-61">[61]</a></sup> Between 1986 and 1993, the unemployment rate rose from 3.6% to 11%.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-69"><a href="#cite_note-69">[69]</a></sup>
</p>
<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a class="mw-file-description" href="/wiki/File:Postal_deregulation_New_Zealand.jpg"><img class="mw-file-element" data-file-height="2304" data-file-width="3072" decoding="async" height="165" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0c/Postal_deregulation_New_Zealand.jpg/220px-Postal_deregulation_New_Zealand.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0c/Postal_deregulation_New_Zealand.jpg/330px-Postal_deregulation_New_Zealand.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0c/Postal_deregulation_New_Zealand.jpg/440px-Postal_deregulation_New_Zealand.jpg 2x" width="220"/></a><figcaption>Since the deregulation of the postal sector, different postal operators can install mail collection boxes in New Zealand's streets</figcaption></figure>
<p>Deregulation also created a business-friendly regulatory framework which has benefited those able to take advantage of it. A 2008 survey in <a href="/wiki/The_Heritage_Foundation" title="The Heritage Foundation">The Heritage Foundation</a> and <i><a href="/wiki/The_Wall_Street_Journal" title="The Wall Street Journal">The Wall Street Journal</a></i> ranked New Zealand 99.9% in "Business freedom", and 80% overall in "Economic freedom", noting that it takes, on average, only 12 days to establish a business in New Zealand, compared with a worldwide average of 43 days.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-70"><a href="#cite_note-70">[70]</a></sup>
</p><p>Deregulation has also been blamed for other significant negative effects. One of these was the <a href="/wiki/Leaky_homes_crisis" title="Leaky homes crisis">leaky homes crisis</a>, whereby the loosening up of building standards (in the expectation that market forces would assure quality) led to many thousands of severely deficient buildings, mostly residential homes and apartments, being constructed over a period of a decade. The costs of fixing the damage has been estimated at over NZ$11 billion (as at 2009<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup>).<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-RUD_71-0"><a href="#cite_note-RUD-71">[71]</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="21st_century">21st century</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: 21st century"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a class="mw-file-description" href="/wiki/File:NzGDPdata_720by540.svg"><img class="mw-file-element" data-file-height="540" data-file-width="720" decoding="async" height="165" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4b/NzGDPdata_720by540.svg/220px-NzGDPdata_720by540.svg.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4b/NzGDPdata_720by540.svg/330px-NzGDPdata_720by540.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4b/NzGDPdata_720by540.svg/440px-NzGDPdata_720by540.svg.png 2x" width="220"/></a><figcaption>New Zealand gross domestic product and net international debt</figcaption></figure><p>Unemployment continued to fall from 1993 to 1994 fiscal year, until the onset of the <a href="/wiki/1997_Asian_financial_crisis" title="1997 Asian financial crisis">1997 Asian financial crisis</a> again pushed the rate higher.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-72"><a href="#cite_note-72">[72]</a></sup> By 2016 the unemployment rate decreased to 5.3 percent, the lowest level in 7 years.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-73"><a href="#cite_note-73">[73]</a></sup>
</p><p>Between 2000 and 2007, the New Zealand economy expanded by an average of 3.5% a year driven primarily by private consumption and the buoyant housing market. During this period, inflation averaged only 2.6%  a year, within the Reserve Bank's target range of 1% to 3%.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-treasury.govt.nz_74-0"><a href="#cite_note-treasury.govt.nz-74">[74]</a></sup> However, in early 2008 the economy entered recession, before the effects of the <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Global_financial_crisis" title="Global financial crisis">global financial crisis</a> (GFC) set in later that year. A drought over the 2007/08 summer led to lower production of dairy products in the first half of 2008. Domestic activity slowed sharply over 2008 as high fuel and food prices dampened domestic consumption, while high interest rates and falling house prices drove a rapid decline in residential investment.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-treasury.govt.nz_74-1"><a href="#cite_note-treasury.govt.nz-74">[74]</a></sup>
</p><p>Around the world instability was developing in the finance sector. This reached a peak in September 2008 when <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Lehman_Brothers_bankruptcy" title="Lehman Brothers bankruptcy">Lehman Brothers</a>, a major American bank, collapsed propelling the world into the global <a href="/wiki/Financial_crisis" title="Financial crisis">financial crisis</a>.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-75"><a href="#cite_note-75">[75]</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span id="Finance_company_collapses_.282006.E2.80.932012.29"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Finance_company_collapses_(2006–2012)">Finance company collapses (2006–2012)</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: Finance company collapses (2006–2012)"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">Main article: <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Finance_company_collapses,_2006%E2%80%932012_(New_Zealand)" title="Finance company collapses, 2006–2012 (New Zealand)">Finance company collapses, 2006–2012 (New Zealand)</a></div>
<figure class="mw-halign-right" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a class="mw-file-description" href="/wiki/File:New_Zealand_bonds.webp"><img class="mw-file-element" data-file-height="1287" data-file-width="5356" decoding="async" height="72" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b0/New_Zealand_bonds.webp/300px-New_Zealand_bonds.webp.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b0/New_Zealand_bonds.webp/450px-New_Zealand_bonds.webp.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b0/New_Zealand_bonds.webp/600px-New_Zealand_bonds.webp.png 2x" width="300"/></a><figcaption>New Zealand bonds <br/> <a href="/wiki/Inverted_yield_curve" title="Inverted yield curve">Inverted yield curve</a> in 1994–1998 and 2004–2008 <link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r981673959" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><div class="legend"><span class="legend-line mw-no-invert" style="display: inline-block; vertical-align: middle; width: 1.67em; height: 0; border-style: none; border-top: 2px dotted black;border-top:#012169 solid 3px;"> </span> 20 year</div> <link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r981673959" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><div class="legend"><span class="legend-line mw-no-invert" style="display: inline-block; vertical-align: middle; width: 1.67em; height: 0; border-style: none; border-top: 2px dotted black;border-top:#61D836 solid 3px;"> </span> 10 year</div> <link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r981673959" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><div class="legend"><span class="legend-line mw-no-invert" style="display: inline-block; vertical-align: middle; width: 1.67em; height: 0; border-style: none; border-top: 2px dotted black;border-top:#929292 solid 3px;"> </span> 2 year</div> <link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r981673959" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><div class="legend"><span class="legend-line mw-no-invert" style="display: inline-block; vertical-align: middle; width: 1.67em; height: 0; border-style: none; border-top: 2px dotted black;border-top:#F8BA00 solid 3px;"> </span> 3 month</div> <link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r981673959" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><div class="legend"><span class="legend-line mw-no-invert" style="display: inline-block; vertical-align: middle; width: 1.67em; height: 0; border-style: none; border-top: 2px dotted black;border-top:#FF2600 solid 3px;"> </span> 1 month</div></figcaption></figure>
<p>Uncertainty began to dominate the global financial and economic environment. Business and consumer confidence in New Zealand plummeted as dozens of finance companies collapsed.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-76"><a href="#cite_note-76">[76]</a></sup> To try and stop a flight of funds from New Zealand institutions to those in Australia, the Government established the <a href="/wiki/Crown_Retail_Deposit_Guarantee_Scheme" title="Crown Retail Deposit Guarantee Scheme">Crown Retail Deposit Guarantee Scheme</a> to cover depositors funds in the event that a bank or finance company went broke.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-77"><a href="#cite_note-77">[77]</a></sup> This protected some investors but nevertheless, at least 67 <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Finance_company_collapses_(New_Zealand)" title="Finance company collapses (New Zealand)">finance companies collapsed</a> within a short period of time.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-78"><a href="#cite_note-78">[78]</a></sup> The largest of these was <a href="/wiki/South_Canterbury_Finance" title="South Canterbury Finance">South Canterbury Finance</a> which cost taxpayers NZ$1.58 billion when the company collapsed in August 2010.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-79"><a href="#cite_note-79">[79]</a></sup> The directors of many of these finance companies were subsequently investigated for fraud and some high-profile directors went to prison.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-80"><a href="#cite_note-80">[80]</a></sup><sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-81"><a href="#cite_note-81">[81]</a></sup><sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-82"><a href="#cite_note-82">[82]</a></sup><sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-83"><a href="#cite_note-83">[83]</a></sup><sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-84"><a href="#cite_note-84">[84]</a></sup>
</p><p>In an attempt to stimulate the economy, the Reserve Bank lowered the Official Cash Rate (OCR) from a high of 8.25% (July 2008) to an all-time low of 2.5% at the end of April 2009.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-treasury.govt.nz_74-2"><a href="#cite_note-treasury.govt.nz-74">[74]</a></sup>
</p><p>Fortunately for New Zealand, the recession was relatively shallow compared to many other nations in the OECD, it was sixth least affected out of the 34 member
nations with negative real GDP growth totaling 3.5%.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-treasury.govt.nz_74-3"><a href="#cite_note-treasury.govt.nz-74">[74]</a></sup> In 2009 the economy picked up, led by strong demand from major trading partners Australia and China, and historically high prices for New Zealand's dairy and log exports. In 2010 the GDP grew by a modest 1.6%, but over the next couple of years economic activity continued to improve, driven by the rebuild in <a href="/wiki/Canterbury_Region" title="Canterbury Region">Canterbury</a> after the <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Christchurch_earthquakes" title="Christchurch earthquakes">Christchurch earthquakes</a> and recovery in domestic demand.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-treasury.govt.nz_74-4"><a href="#cite_note-treasury.govt.nz-74">[74]</a></sup> Through 2011, global conditions deteriorated and the terms of trade eased off their 2011 peak, continuing to moderate until September 2012. Since then, commodity prices have rebounded strongly, with strong demand from China and the international situation improving. Commodity prices have been at record highs in recent quarters and remain elevated. High commodity prices are expected to provide a considerable boost to nominal GDP growth in the near term.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-treasury.govt.nz_74-5"><a href="#cite_note-treasury.govt.nz-74">[74]</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span id=".22Rock_star.22_economy"></span><span class="mw-headline" id='"Rock_star"_economy'>"Rock star" economy</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title='Edit section: "Rock star" economy'><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>In 2013, the economy grew 3.3%. HSBC chief economist for Australia and New Zealand, Paul Bloxham, was so impressed that he predicted New Zealand's growth would outpace most of its peers, and he described New Zealand as the "rock star economy of 2014".<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-85"><a href="#cite_note-85">[85]</a></sup> Another financial commentator said the New Zealand dollar was the "hottest" currency of 2014.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-86"><a href="#cite_note-86">[86]</a></sup> Only three months later, the <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand_Productivity_Commission" title="New Zealand Productivity Commission">New Zealand Productivity Commission</a> expressed concern about low living standards and problems affecting the long-term drivers of growth. Paul Conway, Director of Economics and Research at the Productivity Commission, wrote: "New Zealand's broad policy settings should generate GDP per capita 20 per cent above the OECD average, but the actual result is more than 20 per cent below average. We may be punching above our weight, but that's only because we are in the wrong weight division!"<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-87"><a href="#cite_note-87">[87]</a></sup> In August, Bloxham admitted that "the sharp decline in dairy prices over the last six months has clouded the outlook somewhat".<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-88"><a href="#cite_note-88">[88]</a></sup> In December however Bloxham stated that he thought the New Zealand economy would continue to grow strongly.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-89"><a href="#cite_note-89">[89]</a></sup>
</p><p>In 2014 increased attention was paid to the growing gap between rich and poor. In <i><a href="/wiki/The_Guardian" title="The Guardian">The Guardian</a></i>, Max Rashbrook said policies implemented by both Labour and National governments have increased inequality. He claims that for twenty years outrage "has been muted", but "Alarm bells are finally beginning to sound. Recent polling shows three-quarters of New Zealanders think theirs is no longer an egalitarian country".<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-90"><a href="#cite_note-90">[90]</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span id="2020.E2.80.9322_recession"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="2020–22_recession">2020–22 recession</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: 2020–22 recession"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Economic_impact_of_the_COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_Zealand" title="Economic impact of the COVID-19 pandemic in New Zealand">Economic impact of the COVID-19 pandemic in New Zealand</a></div>
<p>New Zealand recorded its first case of COVID-19 on 28 February 2020. In response to the pandemic, the country closed its borders to everyone except New Zealand citizens and residents on 19 March, and went into full (Level 4) lockdown from 26 March to 27 April, followed by a partial (Level 3) lockdown from 28 April to 13 May.
</p><p>The border closure combined with the lockdowns saw the retail, accommodation, hospitality, and transport sectors experiencing major declines. On 17 September 2020, New Zealand officially entered a recession, with the country's gross domestic product retracting by 12.2% in the June quarter.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-91"><a href="#cite_note-91">[91]</a></sup><sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-92"><a href="#cite_note-92">[92]</a></sup><sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-93"><a href="#cite_note-93">[93]</a></sup> The GDP rebounded 14% in the September quarter to leave a 2.2% year-on-year retraction.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-94"><a href="#cite_note-94">[94]</a></sup>
</p><p>After successfully containing the virus, the New Zealand economy had sharp growth in what is known as a V-shaped recovery and ended the year with an overall economic expansion of 0.4%, better than the predicted 1.7% contraction.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-95"><a href="#cite_note-95">[95]</a></sup> Unemployment also dropped to 4.9% in December 2020, down from a peak Covid effected rate of 5.3% in September.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-96"><a href="#cite_note-96">[96]</a></sup>
</p><p>By 23 September 2021, the Restaurant Association's Chief executive Marisa Bidois estimated that about 1,000 hospitality businesses nationwide had been forced to close as a result of the COVID-19 pandemic, leading to the loss of 13,000 jobs. In response, the Association lobbied the Government for Government for continued wage subsidies and incentives to boost customer rates.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-97"><a href="#cite_note-97">[97]</a></sup> On 13 November 2021, the <i><a href="/wiki/Bay_of_Plenty_Times" title="Bay of Plenty Times">Bay of Plenty Times</a></i> reported that 26,774 companies had been liquidated during the first eight months of 2021.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-98"><a href="#cite_note-98">[98]</a></sup>
</p><p>On 27 January 2022, New Zealand's inflation rate hit a 30-year record high of 5.9% at the end of 2021. According to figures released by Statistics New Zealand, the rising cost of construction, petrol and rents pushed the consumer price index up 1.4 per cent between October and December 2021. Statistics NZ also recorded a two percent increase in household utilities expenses, which was fuelled by the rising costs of new dwellings (which rose by 16% from 2020) and a 30 percent hike in fuel prices (from NZ $1.87 per litre to $2.45 per litre). Prime Minister <a href="/wiki/Jacinda_Ardern" title="Jacinda Ardern">Jacinda Ardern</a> attributed the sharp inflation rate to rising crude oil prices overseas. By contrast, the opposition National Party leader <a href="/wiki/Christopher_Luxon" title="Christopher Luxon">Christopher Luxon</a> and Finance spokesperson <a href="/wiki/Simon_Bridges" title="Simon Bridges">Simon Bridges</a> attributed rising inflation to the Government's alleged "wasteful" spending.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-99"><a href="#cite_note-99">[99]</a></sup>
</p><p>On 1 February 2022, an annual report released by the <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Organisation_of_Economic_Cooperation_and_Development" title="Organisation of Economic Cooperation and Development">Organisation of Economic Cooperation and Development</a> (OECD) identified the country's <a href="/wiki/COVID-19_managed_isolation_in_New_Zealand" title="COVID-19 managed isolation in New Zealand">border restrictions</a> and declining house prices as the main risks facing New Zealand's economy that year. While the OECD report credited New Zealand's <a href="/wiki/COVID-19_alert_levels_in_New_Zealand" title="COVID-19 alert levels in New Zealand">elimination strategy</a> and macroeconomic stimuli such as wage and socio-economic subsidies with helping the economy to bounce back to pre-COVID-19 levels, it also warned that excessive Government spending was causing the economy to overheat and substantial increases in household and government debt. The OECD welcomed the Reserve Bank's decision to raise interest rates but also urged the Government to raise the superannuation age, eliminate obstacles to building houses, and reduce government spending. The OECD also supported the introduction of a social insurance scheme for unemployed workers.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-100"><a href="#cite_note-100">[100]</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Overview">Overview</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: Overview"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a class="mw-file-description" href="/wiki/File:New_Zealand_balance_of_payments_net_international_debt.svg"><img class="mw-file-element" data-file-height="540" data-file-width="720" decoding="async" height="165" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f2/New_Zealand_balance_of_payments_net_international_debt.svg/220px-New_Zealand_balance_of_payments_net_international_debt.svg.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f2/New_Zealand_balance_of_payments_net_international_debt.svg/330px-New_Zealand_balance_of_payments_net_international_debt.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f2/New_Zealand_balance_of_payments_net_international_debt.svg/440px-New_Zealand_balance_of_payments_net_international_debt.svg.png 2x" width="220"/></a><figcaption>New Zealand balance of payments and international investment position - net international debt</figcaption></figure><p>In 2015 the <a href="/wiki/Social_Progress_Index" title="Social Progress Index">Social Progress Index</a>, which covers such areas as <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Basic_human_needs" title="Basic human needs">basic human needs</a>, foundations of well-being, and the level of opportunity available to citizens, ranked the New Zealand economy fifth.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-101"><a href="#cite_note-101">[101]</a></sup> However, the outlook includes some challenges. New Zealand income levels, which used to be above those of many countries in Western Europe prior to the crisis of the 1970s, dropped in relative terms and never recovered. As a result, the number of New Zealanders living in poverty has grown and <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Income_inequality" title="Income inequality">income inequality</a> has increased dramatically.
</p><p>New Zealand has also had persistent <a href="/wiki/Current_account_(balance_of_payments)" title="Current account (balance of payments)">current-account</a> deficits since the early 1970s, peaking at −7.8% of GDP in 2006 but falling to −2.6% of GDP in <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Financial_Year" title="Financial Year">FY</a> 2014.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-national_accounts_march_2014_102-0"><a href="#cite_note-national_accounts_march_2014-102">[102]</a></sup> The CIA World Fact Book estimates New Zealand's 2017 public debt (that owed by the government) at 31.7% of GDP.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-cia_world_factbook_103-0"><a href="#cite_note-cia_world_factbook-103">[103]</a></sup> Between 1984 and 2006, net external foreign debt increased 11-fold, to NZ$182 billion.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-SALE_37-1"><a href="#cite_note-SALE-37">[37]</a></sup> As of   2018<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup> gross core crown debt was NZ$84,524 million or 29.5% of GDP and net core crown debt was NZ$62,114 million or 21.7% of GDP.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-debt_investment_19-1"><a href="#cite_note-debt_investment-19">[19]</a></sup>
</p>
<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a class="mw-file-description" href="/wiki/File:Debt_to_GDP_ratio_New_Zealand_Government_timeseriesnotitle_720by540.svg"><img class="mw-file-element" data-file-height="540" data-file-width="720" decoding="async" height="165" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c5/Debt_to_GDP_ratio_New_Zealand_Government_timeseriesnotitle_720by540.svg/220px-Debt_to_GDP_ratio_New_Zealand_Government_timeseriesnotitle_720by540.svg.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c5/Debt_to_GDP_ratio_New_Zealand_Government_timeseriesnotitle_720by540.svg/330px-Debt_to_GDP_ratio_New_Zealand_Government_timeseriesnotitle_720by540.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c5/Debt_to_GDP_ratio_New_Zealand_Government_timeseriesnotitle_720by540.svg/440px-Debt_to_GDP_ratio_New_Zealand_Government_timeseriesnotitle_720by540.svg.png 2x" width="220"/></a><figcaption>New Zealand Government Gross Debt as percent of GDP 1860 to 2000</figcaption></figure>
<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a class="mw-file-description" href="/wiki/File:GDP_per_capita_development_in_Australia_and_New_Zealand.svg"><img class="mw-file-element" data-file-height="600" data-file-width="850" decoding="async" height="155" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/01/GDP_per_capita_development_in_Australia_and_New_Zealand.svg/220px-GDP_per_capita_development_in_Australia_and_New_Zealand.svg.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/01/GDP_per_capita_development_in_Australia_and_New_Zealand.svg/330px-GDP_per_capita_development_in_Australia_and_New_Zealand.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/01/GDP_per_capita_development_in_Australia_and_New_Zealand.svg/440px-GDP_per_capita_development_in_Australia_and_New_Zealand.svg.png 2x" width="220"/></a><figcaption>GDP per capita development in Australia and New Zealand</figcaption></figure>
<p>Despite New Zealand's persistent current-account deficits, the balance on external goods and services has generally been positive. In FY 2014, export receipts exceeded imports by NZ$3.9 billion.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-national_accounts_march_2014_102-1"><a href="#cite_note-national_accounts_march_2014-102">[102]</a></sup> There has been an investment income imbalance or net outflow for debt-servicing of external loans. In FY 2014, New Zealand's investment income from the rest of the world was NZ$7 billion, versus outgoings of NZ$16.3 billion, a deficit of NZ$9.3 billion.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-national_accounts_march_2014_102-2"><a href="#cite_note-national_accounts_march_2014-102">[102]</a></sup> The proportion of the current-account deficit that is attributable to the investment income imbalance (a net outflow to the Australian-owned banking sector) grew from one third in 1997 to roughly 70% in 2008.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-104"><a href="#cite_note-104">[104]</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Taxation">Taxation</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: Taxation"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Taxation_in_New_Zealand" title="Taxation in New Zealand">Taxation in New Zealand</a></div>
<p>At the national level the <a href="/wiki/Inland_Revenue_Department_(New_Zealand)" title="Inland Revenue Department (New Zealand)">Inland Revenue Department</a> (IRD) collects tax in New Zealand on behalf of the <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand_Government" title="New Zealand Government">New Zealand Government</a>. New Zealanders pay national taxes on personal and <a href="/wiki/Business" title="Business">business</a> income, and on the supply of <a href="/wiki/Goods_and_services" title="Goods and services">goods and services</a> (<a href="/wiki/Goods_and_Services_Tax_(New_Zealand)" title="Goods and Services Tax (New Zealand)">GST</a>). There is no <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Capital-gains_tax" title="Capital-gains tax">capital-gains tax</a>, although certain "gains" such as profits on the sale of patent rights are deemed to be income. Income tax does apply to property transactions in certain circumstances, particularly speculation. <a href="/wiki/Territorial_authorities_of_New_Zealand" title="Territorial authorities of New Zealand">Local authorities</a> manage and collect local property taxes (<a href="/wiki/Rates_(tax)" title="Rates (tax)">rates</a>). Some goods and services carry a specific tax, referred to as an <a href="/wiki/Excise" title="Excise"> excise or a duty</a> such as alcohol excise or gaming duty. These are collected by a range of government agencies such as the <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand_Customs_Service" title="New Zealand Customs Service">New Zealand Customs Service</a>. There is no social security (payroll) tax or land tax in New Zealand.
</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/2010_New_Zealand_budget" title="2010 New Zealand budget">2010 New Zealand budget</a> announced cuts to personal tax-rates, with the top personal tax-rate reduced from 38% to 33%<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-105"><a href="#cite_note-105">[105]</a></sup> The cuts gave New Zealand the second-lowest personal tax burden in the <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Organisation_for_Economic_Co-operation_and_Development" title="Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development">OECD</a>. Only Mexico's citizens retained a higher percentage-wise "take home" proportion of their salaries.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-106"><a href="#cite_note-106">[106]</a></sup>
</p><p>The cuts in income tax were estimated to reduce revenue by $2.46 billion.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-107"><a href="#cite_note-107">[107]</a></sup> To compensate, the National government raised GST from 12.5% to 15%.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-108"><a href="#cite_note-108">[108]</a></sup> Treasury figures show that top income-earners in New Zealand pay between 6% and 8% of their income on GST. Those at the bottom end, earning less than $356 a week, spend between 11% and 14% on GST. Based on these figures, <i><a href="/wiki/The_New_Zealand_Herald" title="The New Zealand Herald">The New Zealand Herald</a></i> predicted that putting GST up to 15% would increase living costs for the poor more than twice as much as for the rich.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-109"><a href="#cite_note-109">[109]</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Corruption">Corruption</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=12" title="Edit section: Corruption"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Corruption_in_New_Zealand" title="Corruption in New Zealand">Corruption in New Zealand</a></div>
<p>New Zealand ranked 1st on the <a href="/wiki/Transparency_International" title="Transparency International">Transparency International</a> <a href="/wiki/Corruption_Perceptions_Index" title="Corruption Perceptions Index">Corruption Perceptions Index</a> (CPI) of 2017 with a score of 89 out of 100.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-110"><a href="#cite_note-110">[110]</a></sup> In 2018 New Zealand ranked 2nd on the Corruption Perceptions Index with a score of 87 out of 100.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-111"><a href="#cite_note-111">[111]</a></sup> In 2019, New Zealand ranked 1st on the Corruption Perceptions Index with a score of 87 out of 100.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-112"><a href="#cite_note-112">[112]</a></sup>
Although New Zealand is one of the least corrupt countries in the world, corruption still exists in New Zealand.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-113"><a href="#cite_note-113">[113]</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Regional_economies">Regional economies</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: Regional economies"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a class="mw-file-description" href="/wiki/File:Regions_of_NZ_Numbered.svg"><img class="mw-file-element" data-file-height="415" data-file-width="290" decoding="async" height="315" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1d/Regions_of_NZ_Numbered.svg/220px-Regions_of_NZ_Numbered.svg.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1d/Regions_of_NZ_Numbered.svg/330px-Regions_of_NZ_Numbered.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1d/Regions_of_NZ_Numbered.svg/440px-Regions_of_NZ_Numbered.svg.png 2x" width="220"/></a><figcaption>Map of <a href="/wiki/Regions_of_New_Zealand" title="Regions of New Zealand">regions of New Zealand</a></figcaption></figure>
