<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Unemployment">Unemployment</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=14" title="Edit section: Unemployment"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Prior to the economic shock created by Britain's decision to join the <a href="/wiki/European_Economic_Community" title="European Economic Community">EEC</a> in 1973, which removed the UK as New Zealand's primary market for exports,<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-117"><a href="#cite_note-117">[115]</a></sup> unemployment in New Zealand was very low. A recession and a collapse in wool prices in 1966 led to unemployment rising by 131%, but still represented only a 0.7% percentage point increase in the unemployment rate.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-dol_unemployment_118-0"><a href="#cite_note-dol_unemployment-118">[116]</a></sup>
</p><p>After 1973, unemployment became a persistent economic and social issue in New Zealand. Recessions from 1976 to 1978 and from 1982 to 1983 greatly increased unemployment again.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-dol_unemployment_118-1"><a href="#cite_note-dol_unemployment-118">[116]</a></sup> Between 1985 and 2012 the unemployment rate averaged 6.29%. After the stock market <a href="/wiki/Black_Monday_(1987)#New_Zealand" title="Black Monday (1987)">crash of 1987</a>, unemployment rose 170%<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-dol_unemployment_118-2"><a href="#cite_note-dol_unemployment-118">[116]</a></sup> reaching an all-time high of 11.20% in September 1991.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-hlfs_December_2015_119-0"><a href="#cite_note-hlfs_December_2015-119">[117]</a></sup> The <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Asian_financial_crisis_of_1997" title="Asian financial crisis of 1997">Asian financial crisis of 1997</a> sent unemployment upwards again, by 28%.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-dol_unemployment_118-3"><a href="#cite_note-dol_unemployment-118">[116]</a></sup> By 2007 it had dropped again and the rate stood at 3.5% (December 2007), its lowest level since the current method of surveying began in 1986. This gave the country the 5th-best ranking in the OECD (with an OECD average at the time of 5.5%). The low numbers correlated with a robust economy and a large backlog of job positions at all levels.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-JOB_120-0"><a href="#cite_note-JOB-120">[118]</a></sup> Unemployment numbers are not always directly comparable between OECD nations, as members do not all keep labour market statistics in the same way.
</p><p>The percentage of the population employed has also increased in recent years, to 68.8% of all inhabitants,<sup class="noprint Inline-Template" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Dates_and_numbers#Chronological_items" title="Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Dates and numbers"><span title="The time period mentioned near this tag is ambiguous. (May 2021)">when?</span></a></i>]</sup> with full-time jobs increasing slightly, and part-time occupations decreasing in turn. The increase in the working population percentage is attributed<sup class="noprint Inline-Template" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Words_to_watch#Unsupported_attributions" title="Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Words to watch"><span title="The material near this tag may use weasel words or too-vague attribution. (May 2021)">by whom?</span></a></i>]</sup> to increasing wages and higher costs of living moving more people into employment.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-JOB_120-1"><a href="#cite_note-JOB-120">[118]</a></sup><sup class="noprint Inline-Template" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability" title="Wikipedia:Verifiability"><span title="The material near this tag failed verification of its source citation(s). (May 2021)">failed verification</span></a></i>]</sup> The low unemployment also had some disadvantages, with many companies unable to fill jobs.
</p><p>From December 2007, mainly as a result of the <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Financial_crisis_of_2007%E2%80%932008" title="Financial crisis of 2007–2008">global financial crisis</a>, unemployment numbers began to rise. This trend continued until September 2012, reaching a high of 6.7%. They began to recover after that point, sitting at 3.9% as of June  2019<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup>.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-121"><a href="#cite_note-121">[119]</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Housing_affordability">Housing affordability</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=15" title="Edit section: Housing affordability"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Housing_in_New_Zealand" title="Housing in New Zealand">Housing in New Zealand</a></div>
<p><a class="new" href="/w/index.php?title=Shamubeel_Eaqub&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" title="Shamubeel Eaqub (page does not exist)">Shamubeel Eaqub</a>, formerly a principal economist at the <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand_Institute_of_Economic_Research" title="New Zealand Institute of Economic Research">New Zealand Institute of Economic Research</a> (NZIER), said in 2014 that thirty years prior, an average house in New Zealand cost two or three times the average household income. House prices rose dramatically in the first years of the 21st century and by 2007, an average house cost more than six times household income.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-nzherald.co.nz_122-0"><a href="#cite_note-nzherald.co.nz-122">[120]</a></sup> International surveys in 2013 showed that housing was unaffordable in all eight of New Zealand's major markets – "unaffordable" being defined as house prices which are more than three times the median regional income.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ReferenceC_123-0"><a href="#cite_note-ReferenceC-123">[121]</a></sup>
</p><p>Demand for property has been strongest in Auckland. In 2014 the average sales price there went from $619,136 to $696,047, a rise of 12% in that 12-month period alone.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-124"><a href="#cite_note-124">[122]</a></sup> In 2015, prices rose another 14%.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-125"><a href="#cite_note-125">[123]</a></sup> This made Auckland New Zealand's least affordable market and one of the most expensive cities in the world<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-126"><a href="#cite_note-126">[124]</a></sup> with houses costing 8 times the average income.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ReferenceC_123-1"><a href="#cite_note-ReferenceC-123">[121]</a></sup> Between 2012 and April 2016, the average Auckland home increased in price by just over two-thirds reaching $931,000 – higher than the cost of an average home in <a href="/wiki/Sydney" title="Sydney">Sydney</a>.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-127"><a href="#cite_note-127">[125]</a></sup>
</p><p>As a result, more people are being priced out of the property market. Those on low incomes are hardest hit, affecting many <a href="/wiki/M%C4%81ori_people" title="Māori people">Maori</a> and <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Pasifika_New_Zealander" title="Pasifika New Zealander">Pasifika</a>. New Zealand's relatively high mortgage-rates are exacerbating the problem<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ReferenceA_128-0"><a href="#cite_note-ReferenceA-128">[126]</a></sup> making it difficult for young people with steady jobs to buy their first home.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-129"><a href="#cite_note-129">[127]</a></sup> According to a 2012 submission made to the Housing Affordability Inquiry,<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-130"><a href="#cite_note-130">[128]</a></sup> escalating house prices are also impacting on many middle income groups, especially those with large families.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-131"><a href="#cite_note-131">[129]</a></sup> Mortgage adviser Bruce Patten said the trend was "disturbing" and added to the gap between the "haves and have-nots".<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-132"><a href="#cite_note-132">[130]</a></sup>
</p><p>Property-analysis company <a href="/wiki/CoreLogic" title="CoreLogic">CoreLogic</a> said<sup class="noprint Inline-Template" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Dates_and_numbers#Chronological_items" title="Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Dates and numbers"><span title="The time period mentioned near this tag is ambiguous. (May 2021)">when?</span></a></i>]</sup> that 45% of house purchases in New Zealand are now made by investors who already own a home, while another 28% are made by people moving from one property to another. Approximately 8% of purchases go to overseas-based cash buyers<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-nzherald.co.nz_122-1"><a href="#cite_note-nzherald.co.nz-122">[120]</a></sup> – primarily Australians, Chinese, and British – although most<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Dates_and_numbers" title="Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Dates and numbers"><span title="This term requires quantification. (May 2021)">quantify</span></a></i>]</sup> economists believe that foreign investment is currently<sup class="noprint Inline-Template" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Dates_and_numbers#Chronological_items" title="Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Dates and numbers"><span title="The time period mentioned near this tag is ambiguous. (May 2021)">when?</span></a></i>]</sup> too small to have a significant effect on property prices.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-133"><a href="#cite_note-133">[131]</a></sup>
</p><p>Whether purchases are made by New Zealanders or by foreigners, it is generally those who are already well off who are buying the bulk of properties on the market. This has had a dramatic effect on home-ownership rates by Kiwis, now<sup class="noprint Inline-Template" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Dates_and_numbers#Chronological_items" title="Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Dates and numbers"><span title="The time period mentioned near this tag is ambiguous. (May 2021)">when?</span></a></i>]</sup> at its lowest level since 1951. Even as recently as 1991, 76% of New Zealand homes were occupied by their owners. By 2013, this had reduced to 63%,<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-134"><a href="#cite_note-134">[132]</a></sup> indicating that more and more people are having to rent.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (May 2021)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> Raewyn Cox, chief executive of the Federation of Family Budgeting, says: "High prices and high interest rates (have) sentenced a rising number of New Zealanders to be lifetime tenants" where they are "stuck in expensive rental situations, heading towards retirement."<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ReferenceA_128-1"><a href="#cite_note-ReferenceA-128">[126]</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Inequality">Inequality</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=16" title="Edit section: Inequality"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Economic_inequality_in_New_Zealand" title="Economic inequality in New Zealand">Economic inequality in New Zealand</a></div>
<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a class="mw-file-description" href="/wiki/File:State_Housing_in_Oranga,_Auckland,_1947.jpg"><img class="mw-file-element" data-file-height="600" data-file-width="800" decoding="async" height="165" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/60/State_Housing_in_Oranga%2C_Auckland%2C_1947.jpg/220px-State_Housing_in_Oranga%2C_Auckland%2C_1947.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/60/State_Housing_in_Oranga%2C_Auckland%2C_1947.jpg/330px-State_Housing_in_Oranga%2C_Auckland%2C_1947.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/60/State_Housing_in_Oranga%2C_Auckland%2C_1947.jpg/440px-State_Housing_in_Oranga%2C_Auckland%2C_1947.jpg 2x" width="220"/></a><figcaption>An egalitarian New Zealand was briefly realised in the <a href="/wiki/Interwar_period" title="Interwar period">interwar</a> and <a href="/wiki/Post-war" title="Post-war">post-war</a> periods, when successive governments sponsored a massive <a href="/wiki/State_housing_in_New_Zealand" title="State housing in New Zealand">state housing</a> programme</figcaption></figure>
<p>Between 1982 and 2011 New Zealand's <a href="/wiki/Gross_domestic_product" title="Gross domestic product">gross domestic product</a> grew by 35%. Almost half of that increase went to a small group who were already the richest in the country. During this period, the average income of the top 10% of earners in New Zealand (those earning more than $72,000)<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-NZ_income_gap_at_crisis_level_135-0"><a href="#cite_note-NZ_income_gap_at_crisis_level-135">[133]</a></sup> almost doubled going from $56,300 to $100,200. The average income of the poorest tenth increased by 13% from $9700 to $11,000.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Paradise_for_a_few_136-0"><a href="#cite_note-Paradise_for_a_few-136">[134]</a></sup>
</p><p><a href="/wiki/Statistics_New_Zealand" title="Statistics New Zealand">Statistics New Zealand</a>, which keeps track of income disparity using the P80/20 ratio, confirms the increase in income  inequality. The ratio shows the difference between high household incomes (those in the 80th percentile) and low household incomes (those in the 20th percentile). The inequality ratio increased between 1988 and 2004, and decreased until the onset of the Global Financial Crisis in 2008, increasing again to 2011 and then declining again from then. By 2013 the disposable income of high-income households was more than two-and-a-half times larger than that of low-income households.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-137"><a href="#cite_note-137">[135]</a></sup> Highlighting the disparity, the top 1% of the population now<sup class="noprint Inline-Template" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Dates_and_numbers#Chronological_items" title="Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Dates and numbers"><span title="The time period mentioned near this tag is ambiguous. (May 2021)">when?</span></a></i>]</sup> owns 16% of the country's wealth<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (May 2021)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> – the richest at one point 5% owned 38%<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-138"><a href="#cite_note-138">[136]</a></sup> – while half the population, including beneficiaries and pensioners, earn less than $24,000.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-NZ_income_gap_at_crisis_level_135-1"><a href="#cite_note-NZ_income_gap_at_crisis_level-135">[133]</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Superannuation">Superannuation</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=17" title="Edit section: Superannuation"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Welfare_in_New_Zealand#Pensions" title="Welfare in New Zealand">Welfare in New Zealand § Pensions</a></div>
<p>New Zealand has a universal <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Superannuation" title="Superannuation">superannuation</a> scheme. Only people who are aged 65 years old or over, is a New Zealand citizen or permanent resident and who is residing in New Zealand at the time of application is eligible. They must also have lived in New Zealand for at least 10 years since they turned 20 with five of those years being since they turned 50. Time spent overseas in certain countries and for certain reasons may be counted for New Zealand superannuation. New Zealand superannuation is taxed, the rate of which depends on superannuitants' other income. The amount of superannuation paid depends on the person's household situation. For a married couple the net tax amount is set by legislation to be no less than 66% of net average wage.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-139"><a href="#cite_note-139">[137]</a></sup>
</p><p>Because of the growing number of elderly becoming eligible, superannuation costs rose from $7.3 billion a year in 2008 to $10.2 billion in 2014.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-140"><a href="#cite_note-140">[138]</a></sup> In 2011 there were twice as many children in New Zealand as elderly (65 and over); by 2051 there are projected to be 60% more elderly than children. In the ten years from 2014, the number of New Zealanders over the age of 65 was projected to grow by about 200,000.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-141"><a href="#cite_note-141">[139]</a></sup>
</p><p>This poses a significant problem for superannuation. The government gradually increased the age of eligibility from 61 to 65 between 1993 and 2001.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-142"><a href="#cite_note-142">[140]</a></sup> In that year the <a href="/wiki/Fifth_Labour_Government_of_New_Zealand" title="Fifth Labour Government of New Zealand">Labour Government</a> of <a href="/wiki/Helen_Clark" title="Helen Clark">Helen Clark</a> introduced the <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand_Superannuation_Fund" title="New Zealand Superannuation Fund">New Zealand Superannuation Fund</a> (known as the "Cullen Fund" after Minister of Finance <a href="/wiki/Michael_Cullen_(politician)" title="Michael Cullen (politician)">Michael Cullen</a>) to part-fund the superannuation scheme into the future. As at October 2014, the fund managed NZ$27.11 billion, 15.9% of which it invested within New Zealand.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-143"><a href="#cite_note-143">[141]</a></sup>
</p><p>In 2007 the same Government introduced a new individual saving-scheme, known as <a href="/wiki/KiwiSaver" title="KiwiSaver">KiwiSaver</a>. KiwiSaver principally targets growing people's retirement savings, but younger participants can also use it to save a deposit for their first home. The scheme is voluntary, work-based and managed by private-sector companies called "KiwiSaver providers". As of   2014<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup> KiwiSaver had 2.3 million active members (60.9% of New Zealand's population under 65). NZ$4 billion was contributed annually, and a total of NZ$19.1 billion has been contributed since 2007.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-KSstats_144-0"><a href="#cite_note-KSstats-144">[142]</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Consumption">Consumption</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=18" title="Edit section: Consumption"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r1097763485">.mw-parser-output .ambox{border:1px solid #a2a9b1;border-left:10px solid #36c;background-color:#fbfbfb;box-sizing:border-box}.mw-parser-output .ambox+.mw-empty-elt+link+style+.ambox,.mw-parser-output .ambox+.mw-empty-elt+link+link+.ambox{margin-top:-1px}html body.mediawiki .mw-parser-output .ambox.mbox-small-left{margin:4px 1em 4px ambox-content" role="presentation"><tbody><tr><td class="mbox-image"><span typeof="mw:File"><a class="mw-file-description" href="/wiki/File:Wiki_letter_w_cropped.svg"><img alt="[icon]" <p>New Zealanders see themselves as <a href="/wiki/First_World" title="First World">first-world</a> <a href="/wiki/Consumer" title="Consumer">consumers</a> with first-world tastes and habits - mitigated only slightly by the country's remoteness from main global producers.
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Infrastructure">Infrastructure</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=19" title="Edit section: Infrastructure"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>According to the National Infrastructure Unit of the Treasury, New Zealand "...continues to face challenges to its infrastructure; all forms of infrastructure are long-term investments, and change does not come about easily or quickly."<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-145"><a href="#cite_note-145">[143]</a></sup> A report prepared for the Association of Consulting and Engineering New Zealand in 2020 claimed that there was an infrastructure deficit of $75<span class="nowrap"> </span> billion (about one quarter of GDP), following decades of under-investment that began in the 1980s.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-146"><a href="#cite_note-146">[144]</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Transport">Transport</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=20" title="Edit section: Transport"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Transport_in_New_Zealand" title="Transport in New Zealand">Transport in New Zealand</a></div>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a class="mw-file-description" href="/wiki/File:Wellington_infrastructure.jpg"><img class="mw-file-element" data-file-height="1944" data-file-width="2592" decoding="async" height="165" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/89/Wellington_infrastructure.jpg/220px-Wellington_infrastructure.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/89/Wellington_infrastructure.jpg/330px-Wellington_infrastructure.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/89/Wellington_infrastructure.jpg/440px-Wellington_infrastructure.jpg 2x" width="220"/></a><figcaption>Highways, rail lines and an inter-island ferry in central Wellington</figcaption></figure>
<p>New Zealand's transport infrastructure is "generally well developed."<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-transport_infrastructure_147-0"><a href="#cite_note-transport_infrastructure-147">[145]</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Road_network">Road network</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=21" title="Edit section: Road network"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">Main article: <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand_state_highway_network" title="New Zealand state highway network">New Zealand state highway network</a></div>
<p>The New Zealand state highway network consists of 11,000 km of road, with 5981.3 km in the <a href="/wiki/North_Island" title="North Island">North Island</a> and 4924.4 km in the <a href="/wiki/South_Island" title="South Island">South Island</a>, built and maintained by the <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/NZ_Transport_Agency" title="NZ Transport Agency">NZ Transport Agency</a>, and paid for from general taxation and fuel excise duty. Heavy road users must pay Road User Charges as well, there is limited use of tolling on state highways. There is also 83,000 km of local roads built and maintained by local authorities.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-148"><a href="#cite_note-148">[146]</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Railway_network">Railway network</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=22" title="Edit section: Railway network"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Rail_transport_in_New_Zealand" title="Rail transport in New Zealand">Rail transport in New Zealand</a></div>
<p>The railway network is owned by <a href="/wiki/State-owned_enterprise" title="State-owned enterprise">state-owned enterprise</a> <a href="/wiki/KiwiRail" title="KiwiRail">KiwiRail</a> and consists of 3,898 km of railway line, built to the <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Narrow_gauge_railways" title="Narrow gauge railways">narrow gauge</a> of <span class="nowrap">1,067 mm</span> (<span class="nowrap">3 ft 6 in</span>).<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-transport_infrastructure_147-1"><a href="#cite_note-transport_infrastructure-147">[145]</a></sup> Of this, 506 km is <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Railway_electrification_system" title="Railway electrification system">electrified</a>.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-transport-m2nz_149-0"><a href="#cite_note-transport-m2nz-149">[147]</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Airways">Airways</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=23" title="Edit section: Airways"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">Main article: <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Airports_in_New_Zealand" title="Airports in New Zealand">Airports in New Zealand</a></div>
<p>There are seven international airports and twenty-eight domestic airports.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-transport_infrastructure_147-2"><a href="#cite_note-transport_infrastructure-147">[145]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Air_New_Zealand" title="Air New Zealand">Air New Zealand</a>, 52% government-owned,<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-150"><a href="#cite_note-150">[148]</a></sup> is the <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/National_carrier" title="National carrier">national carrier</a> and a <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Government-owned_corporation" title="Government-owned corporation">state owned enterprise</a>. <a href="/wiki/Airways_New_Zealand" title="Airways New Zealand">Airways New Zealand</a>, another state owned enterprise, provides air traffic control and communications.
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Seaports">Seaports</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=24" title="Edit section: Seaports"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>New Zealand has 14 international seaports.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-transport_infrastructure_147-3"><a href="#cite_note-transport_infrastructure-147">[145]</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Telecommunications">Telecommunications</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=25" title="Edit section: Telecommunications"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a class="mw-file-description" href="/wiki/File:24_Dunedin_Town_Hall_at_the_Octagon_square,_Dunedin,_New_Zealand.JPG"><img class="mw-file-element" data-file-height="1920" data-file-width="1280" decoding="async" height="330" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/28/24_Dunedin_Town_Hall_at_the_Octagon_square%2C_Dunedin%2C_New_Zealand.JPG/220px-24_Dunedin_Town_Hall_at_the_Octagon_square%2C_Dunedin%2C_New_Zealand.JPG" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/28/24_Dunedin_Town_Hall_at_the_Octagon_square%2C_Dunedin%2C_New_Zealand.JPG/330px-24_Dunedin_Town_Hall_at_the_Octagon_square%2C_Dunedin%2C_New_Zealand.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/28/24_Dunedin_Town_Hall_at_the_Octagon_square%2C_Dunedin%2C_New_Zealand.JPG/440px-24_Dunedin_Town_Hall_at_the_Octagon_square%2C_Dunedin%2C_New_Zealand.JPG 2x" width="220"/></a><figcaption>Telephone booths in <a href="/wiki/Dunedin" title="Dunedin">Dunedin</a></figcaption></figure>
<link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Telecommunications_in_New_Zealand" title="Telecommunications in New Zealand">Telecommunications in New Zealand</a></div>
<p>Present-day telecommunications in New Zealand include telephony, <a href="/wiki/Radio_in_New_Zealand" title="Radio in New Zealand">radio</a>, <a href="/wiki/Television_in_New_Zealand" title="Television in New Zealand">television</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Internet_in_New_Zealand" title="Internet in New Zealand">internet</a> usage. A competitive telecommunications market has seen mobile prices drop to some of the lowest in the OECD.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-151"><a href="#cite_note-151">[149]</a></sup> The copper wire and fibre cable networks are mostly owned by <a href="/wiki/Chorus_Limited" title="Chorus Limited">Chorus Limited</a>, a publicly listed company. Chorus wholesales services to retail providers (such as <a href="/wiki/Spark_New_Zealand" title="Spark New Zealand">Spark</a>). In the mobile sector, there are three operators: Spark, <a href="/wiki/One_NZ" title="One NZ">One NZ</a> and <a href="/wiki/2degrees" title="2degrees">2degrees</a>.
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Internet">Internet</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=26" title="Edit section: Internet"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Internet_in_New_Zealand" title="Internet in New Zealand">Internet in New Zealand</a></div>
<p>New Zealand has a high rate of internet use. As of October 2014<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup>, there are 1,916,000 broadband connections and 65,000 dial-up connections in New Zealand, of which 1,595,000 are residential and 386,000 are business or government.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-stats_152-0"><a href="#cite_note-stats-152">[150]</a></sup> The majority of connections are <a href="/wiki/Digital_subscriber_line" title="Digital subscriber line">digital subscriber line</a> over phone lines.
</p><p>The Government has two plans to bring <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Ultra-Fast_Broadband" title="Ultra-Fast Broadband">Ultra-Fast Broadband</a> to 97.8% of the population by 2019, and is spending NZ$1.35 billion on public-private partnerships to roll out fibre-to-the-home connection in all main towns and cities with population over 10,000. The program aims to deliver ultra-fast broadband capable of at least 100 Mbit/s download and 50 Mbit/s upload to 75% of New Zealanders by 2019.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-153"><a href="#cite_note-153">[151]</a></sup> In total, 1,340,000 households in 26 towns and cities will be connected.
</p><p>Gigabit internet (1000 Mbit/s download speeds) was made available to the entire Ultra-Fast Broadband (UFB) footprint on 1 October 2016, in an announcement from Chorus.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-154"><a href="#cite_note-154">[152]</a></sup>
</p><p>A$300 million Rural Broadband Initiative (RBI) has also been introduced by the Government, with the aim to bring broadband of at least 5 Mbit/s to 86% of rural customers by 2016.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-mbie-rbi_155-0"><a href="#cite_note-mbie-rbi-155">[153]</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Energy">Energy</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=27" title="Edit section: Energy"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Energy_in_New_Zealand" title="Energy in New Zealand">Energy in New Zealand</a></div>
<p>From 1995 to 2013, the energy intensity of the economy per unit of GDP declined by 25 percent.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Energy2014_156-0"><a href="#cite_note-Energy2014-156">[154]</a></sup> A contributing factor is the growth of relatively less energy-intensive service industries.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-157"><a href="#cite_note-157">[155]</a></sup> New Zealand will be potentially among the main winners after the global transition to renewable energy is completed; the country is placed very high – no. 5 among 156 countries – in the index of geopolitical gains and losses after <a href="/wiki/Energy_transition" title="Energy transition">energy transition</a> (GeGaLo Index).<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-158"><a href="#cite_note-158">[156]</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Electricity">Electricity</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=28" title="Edit section: Electricity"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">Main articles: <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand_electricity_market" title="New Zealand electricity market">New Zealand electricity market</a> and <a href="/wiki/Electricity_sector_in_New_Zealand" title="Electricity sector in New Zealand">Electricity sector in New Zealand</a></div>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Electricity_market" title="Electricity market">electricity market</a> is regulated by the Electricity Industry Participation Code administered by the <a href="/wiki/Electricity_Authority_(New_Zealand)" title="Electricity Authority (New Zealand)">Electricity Authority</a> (EA).<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-159"><a href="#cite_note-159">[157]</a></sup> The electricity sector uses mainly <a href="/wiki/Renewable_energy" title="Renewable energy">renewable energy sources</a> such as <a href="/wiki/Hydroelectricity" title="Hydroelectricity">hydropower</a>, <a href="/wiki/Geothermal_energy" title="Geothermal energy">geothermal power</a> and increasingly <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Wind_energy" title="Wind energy">wind energy</a>.
</p><p>The 83% share of renewable energy sources<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-nzcpe_160-0"><a href="#cite_note-nzcpe-160">[158]</a></sup> makes New Zealand one of the most <a href="/wiki/Sustainable_energy" title="Sustainable energy">sustainable</a> economies in terms of electricity generation;<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-161"><a href="#cite_note-161">[159]</a></sup> in terms of total energy consumption in the New Zealand economy, this represents the 30% that comes from renewable sources.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-162"><a href="#cite_note-162">[160]</a></sup> New Zealand suffers from a geographical imbalance between electricity production and consumption. The most substantial electricity generation (both existing and as remaining potential) is located on the South Island and to a lesser degree in the central North Island, while the main demand (which is continuing to grow) is in the northern North Island, particularly the <a href="/wiki/Auckland_Region" title="Auckland Region">Auckland Region</a>. This requires electricity to be transmitted north through a power grid which is reaching its capacity more often.
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Water">Water</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=29" title="Edit section: Water"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Water_supply_and_sanitation_in_New_Zealand" title="Water supply and sanitation in New Zealand">Water supply and sanitation in New Zealand</a></div>
<p>As of 2021, almost all of the three waters assets (drinking water, stormwater and wastewater) are owned by local councils and territorial authorities. There are currently 67 different asset-owning organisations in total.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-dia_163-0"><a href="#cite_note-dia-163">[161]</a></sup>
</p><p>The challenges for local government include funding infrastructure deficits and preparing for large re-investments that are estimated to require $110<span class="nowrap"> </span>billion over the next 30 to 40 years.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-164"><a href="#cite_note-164">[162]</a></sup> There are also significant challenges in meeting statutory requirements for the safety of drinking water, and the environmental expectations for management of stormwater and wastewater. <a href="/wiki/Climate_change_adaptation" title="Climate change adaptation">Climate change adaptation</a>, and providing for population growth add to these challenges.
</p><p>A nationwide reform programme is underway, with the intention of amalgamating the three waters assets into a small number of large regional publicly owned utilities.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-dia_163-1"><a href="#cite_note-dia-163">[161]</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Trade">Trade</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=30" title="Edit section: Trade"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1097763485" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><table class="box-Update plainlinks metadata ambox ambox-content ambox-Update" role="presentation"><tbody><tr><td class="mbox-image"><div class="mbox-image-div"><span typeof="mw:File"><span><img alt="" class="mw-file-element" data-file-height="290" data-file-width="360" decoding="async" height="34" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bd/Ambox_current_red_Asia_Australia.svg/42px-Ambox_current_red_Asia_Australia.svg.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bd/Ambox_current_red_Asia_Australia.svg/63px-Ambox_current_red_Asia_Australia.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bd/Ambox_current_red_Asia_Australia.svg/84px-Ambox_current_red_Asia_Australia.svg.png 2x" width="42"/></span></span></div></td><td class="mbox-text"><div class="mbox-text-span">This section needs to be <b>updated</b>.<span class="hide-when-compact"> Please help update this article to reflect recent events or newly available information.</span> <span class="date-container"><i>(<span class="date">June 2023</span>)</i></span></div></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>New Zealand's small size and long distances from major world markets creates significant challenges in its ability to compete in global markets. In 2018, New Zealand's main trading partners were <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/People%27s_Republic_of_China" title="People's Republic of China">China</a>, <a href="/wiki/Australia" title="Australia">Australia</a>, the <a href="/wiki/European_Union" title="European Union">European Union</a>, the <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a> and <a href="/wiki/Japan" title="Japan">Japan</a>. Together, these five partners account for 66% of New Zealand's two-way trade.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-GSTC_StatNZ_165-0"><a href="#cite_note-GSTC_StatNZ-165">[163]</a></sup><sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-trading_partners_166-0"><a href="#cite_note-trading_partners-166">[164]</a></sup> In March 2014, the total value of goods exported from New Zealand topped $50 billion for the first time, up from $30 billion in 2001.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-167"><a href="#cite_note-167">[165]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand_Trade_and_Enterprise" title="New Zealand Trade and Enterprise">New Zealand Trade and Enterprise</a> (NZTE) offers strategic advice and support to New Zealand businesses wanting to export goods and services to other countries.
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Trade_agreements">Trade agreements</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=31" title="Edit section: Trade agreements"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">Main article: <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/New_Zealand_free_trade_agreements" title="New Zealand free trade agreements">New Zealand free trade agreements</a></div>
<figure class="mw-halign-right" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a class="mw-file-description" href="/wiki/File:Map_of_countries_with_which_New_Zealand_has_free_trade_agreements.svg"><img class="mw-file-element" data-file-height="1398" data-file-width="2754" decoding="async" height="152" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/83/Map_of_countries_with_which_New_Zealand_has_free_trade_agreements.svg/300px-Map_of_countries_with_which_New_Zealand_has_free_trade_agreements.svg.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/83/Map_of_countries_with_which_New_Zealand_has_free_trade_agreements.svg/450px-Map_of_countries_with_which_New_Zealand_has_free_trade_agreements.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/83/Map_of_countries_with_which_New_Zealand_has_free_trade_agreements.svg/600px-Map_of_countries_with_which_New_Zealand_has_free_trade_agreements.svg.png 2x" width="300"/></a><figcaption><table style="width:100%; vertical-align:top; border:1px solid #ABD5F5; background-color:#F1F5FC; margin-top:2px;"> <tbody><tr> <td> <link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r981673959" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><div class="legend"><span class="legend-color mw-no-invert" style="background-color:#ff0000; color:black;"> </span> New Zealand</div><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r981673959" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><div class="legend"><span class="legend-color mw-no-invert" style="background-color:#00bf00ff; color:;"> </span> Free trade agreements in force</div><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r981673959" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><div class="legend"><span class="legend-color mw-no-invert" style="background-color:#ffcc00ff; color:;"> </span> Free trade agreements concluded but not in force</div> </td></tr></tbody></table></figcaption></figure>
<p>Since 1960s New Zealand has pursued free trade agreements with many countries to diversify its export markets and increase the competitiveness of New Zealand's exports to the world.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-FTA_168-0"><a href="#cite_note-FTA-168">[166]</a></sup> As well as reducing barriers to trade, Trade Agreements New Zealand has entered into are designed to ensure existing access is maintained. Trade agreements establish rules by which trade can take place and ensure regulators and officials in countries New Zealand is trading with work closely together.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-FTA_168-1"><a href="#cite_note-FTA-168">[166]</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="China">China</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=32" title="Edit section: China"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>China is New Zealand's largest trading partner, buying primarily meat, dairy products and pine logs. In 2013, trade between New Zealand and China was worth NZ$16.8 billion.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-trading_partners_166-1"><a href="#cite_note-trading_partners-166">[164]</a></sup> This has occurred primarily because of soaring demand for imported dairy products, following the <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Chinese_milk_scandal" title="Chinese milk scandal">Chinese milk scandal</a> in 2008. Since then demand for milk products has been so strong that in the 12 months to March 2014, there was a 51% increase in total exports to China.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-169"><a href="#cite_note-169">[167]</a></sup> The increase was facilitated by the <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand%E2%80%93China_Free_Trade_Agreement" title="New Zealand–China Free Trade Agreement">New Zealand–China Free Trade Agreement</a> which came into force on 1 October 2008. Since that year exports to China have more than tripled.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-170"><a href="#cite_note-170">[168]</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Australia">Australia</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=33" title="Edit section: Australia"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a class="mw-file-description" href="/wiki/File:Australia_New_Zealand_Closer_Economic_Relations_Trade_Agreement_1983_-_signed_by_Laurie_Francis_%26_Lionel_Bowen_(13272074365_cropped).jpg"><img class="mw-file-element" data-file-height="1726" data-file-width="2295" decoding="async" height="165" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d9/Australia_New_Zealand_Closer_Economic_Relations_Trade_Agreement_1983_-_signed_by_Laurie_Francis_%26_Lionel_Bowen_%2813272074365_cropped%29.jpg/220px-Australia_New_Zealand_Closer_Economic_Relations_Trade_Agreement_1983_-_signed_by_Laurie_Francis_%26_Lionel_Bowen_%2813272074365_cropped%29.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d9/Australia_New_Zealand_Closer_Economic_Relations_Trade_Agreement_1983_-_signed_by_Laurie_Francis_%26_Lionel_Bowen_%2813272074365_cropped%29.jpg/330px-Australia_New_Zealand_Closer_Economic_Relations_Trade_Agreement_1983_-_signed_by_Laurie_Francis_%26_Lionel_Bowen_%2813272074365_cropped%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d9/Australia_New_Zealand_Closer_Economic_Relations_Trade_Agreement_1983_-_signed_by_Laurie_Francis_%26_Lionel_Bowen_%2813272074365_cropped%29.jpg/440px-Australia_New_Zealand_Closer_Economic_Relations_Trade_Agreement_1983_-_signed_by_Laurie_Francis_%26_Lionel_Bowen_%2813272074365_cropped%29.jpg 2x" width="220"/></a><figcaption>Australia New Zealand Closer Economic Relations Trade Agreement 28 March 1983 – signed by Laurie Francis &amp; Lionel Brown</figcaption></figure>
<p>Australia was New Zealand's largest bilateral trading partner in 2013, when trade between the two countries was worth NZ$25.6 billion,<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-trading_partners_166-2"><a href="#cite_note-trading_partners-166">[164]</a></sup> and before China overtook Australia. Economic and trading links between Australia and New Zealand are underpinned by the "<a href="/wiki/Closer_Economic_Relations" title="Closer Economic Relations">Closer Economic Relations</a>" (CER) agreement, which allows for free trade in goods and most services. Since 1990, CER has created a single market of more than 25 million people. Australia is now the destination of 19% of New Zealand's exports, including light crude oil, gold, wine, cheese and timber, as well as a wide range of manufactured items.
</p><p>The CER also creates a free labour market which allows New Zealand and Australian citizens to live and work freely in each other's country together with mutual recognition of professional qualifications. This means individuals who are registered to practise an occupation in one country can register to practise an equivalent occupation in the other country. Banking regulation and supervision are co-ordinated through the Trans-Tasman Council on Banking Supervision and there are also ongoing discussions about co-ordinating Australian and New Zealand business law.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Principal_Trading_Partners_171-0"><a href="#cite_note-Principal_Trading_Partners-171">[169]</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="European_Union">European Union</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=34" title="Edit section: European Union"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>The European Union is New Zealand's third largest trading partner. A growing number of New Zealand companies use the United Kingdom as a base to supply their products to the European market.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-172"><a href="#cite_note-172">[170]</a></sup> However trade with the European Union is declining as demand from Asia continues to grow. The EU takes only 8% of New Zealand exports but provides around 12% of imports.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Principal_Trading_Partners_171-1"><a href="#cite_note-Principal_Trading_Partners-171">[169]</a></sup>
</p><p>In July 2014, negotiations on the Partnership Agreement on Relations and Cooperation (PARC) between New Zealand and the European Union were concluded.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-173"><a href="#cite_note-173">[171]</a></sup> The agreement covers the trade and economic relationship between the EU and New Zealand with a view to further liberalisation of trade and investment and acknowledges the intention of the European Union to upgrade its diplomatic presence in New Zealand with a resident ambassador.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-174"><a href="#cite_note-174">[172]</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="United_States">United States</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=35" title="Edit section: United States"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>The United States was New Zealand's third largest trading partner in 2013, when bilateral trade between the two countries was valued at NZ$11.8 billion,<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-trading_partners_166-3"><a href="#cite_note-trading_partners-166">[164]</a></sup> and before it was overtaken by the EU. New Zealand's main exports to the United States are beef, dairy products and lamb. Imports from the US include specialised machinery, pharmaceutical products, oil and fuel. In addition to trade, there is a high level of corporate and individual investment between the two countries and the US is a major source of tourists coming to New Zealand. In March 2012, the United States had a total of $44 billion invested in New Zealand.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-175"><a href="#cite_note-175">[173]</a></sup> A number of US companies have subsidiary branches in New Zealand. Many operate through local agents, with some joint venture associations. The <a href="/wiki/United_States_Chamber_of_Commerce" title="United States Chamber of Commerce">United States Chamber of Commerce</a> is active in New Zealand, with a main office in <a href="/wiki/Auckland" title="Auckland">Auckland</a> and a branch committee in Wellington.
</p><p>According to the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, New Zealand and the United States "share a deep and longstanding friendship based on a common heritage, shared values and interests, and a commitment to promoting a free, democratic, secure and prosperous world".<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-176"><a href="#cite_note-176">[174]</a></sup> This common background has not translated into a free trade agreement between the two countries.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-177"><a href="#cite_note-177">[175]</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Japan_and_other_Asian_economies">Japan and other Asian economies</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=36" title="Edit section: Japan and other Asian economies"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Japan is New Zealand's fifth largest trading partner. In the 21st century, Asian economies have been developing rapidly providing significant demand for New Zealand's exports. New Zealand also trades with Taiwan, Hong Kong, Malaysia, Indonesia, Singapore, Thailand, India and the Philippines and this now accounts for around 16% of total exports.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Principal_Trading_Partners_171-2"><a href="#cite_note-Principal_Trading_Partners-171">[169]</a></sup> New Zealand initiated a <a href="/wiki/Free_trade_agreement" title="Free trade agreement">free trade agreement</a> with Singapore in September 2000 which was extended in 2005 to include Chile and Brunei and is now known as the <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Trans-Pacific_Strategic_Economic_Partnership" title="Trans-Pacific Strategic Economic Partnership">P4 agreement</a>.
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Relationship_with_Pacific_Islands">Relationship with Pacific Islands</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=37" title="Edit section: Relationship with Pacific Islands"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>The Pacific region with numerous islands is New Zealand's sixth largest trading market and is growing every year. In 2011 exports to Pacific Islands were worth over $1.5 billion up 12% on the previous year. Fiji is the biggest individual market followed very closely by Papua New Guinea, French Polynesia and New Caledonia. Goods exported to the islands include refined oil, construction materials, medicines, sheep meat, milk, butter, fruit and vegetables.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-178"><a href="#cite_note-178">[176]</a></sup> New Zealand also assists Pacific Islands with defence and regional security, and with management of the environment and fisheries.
</p><p>Because of their small size, the Pacific Islands are some of the most vulnerable environments in the world and are on the receiving end of numerous cyclones every year. When disasters occur, they often have severe social and economic effects which last for years. Since 1992, New Zealand has co-operated with Australia and France to respond to disasters in the Pacific. New Zealand provides emergency supplies and transport, funding for roading and housing and the deployment of specialists to affected areas.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-179"><a href="#cite_note-179">[177]</a></sup>
</p><p>Through the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Trade, New Zealand also provides international aid and development funding to help stimulate sustainable economic development in underdeveloped economies. The New Zealand Aid Programme, allocated about $550m a year, is focused primarily on promoting development in the Pacific. The allocation of $550 million represents about 0.26% of New Zealand's <a href="/wiki/Gross_national_income" title="Gross national income">gross national income</a> (GNI).<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-180"><a href="#cite_note-180">[178]</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Foreign_investment">Foreign investment</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=38" title="Edit section: Foreign investment"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>New Zealand welcomes and encourages foreign investment, which is overseen by the <a href="/wiki/Overseas_Investment_Office" title="Overseas Investment Office">Overseas Investment Office</a>. In 2014 foreign direct investment totalled NZ$107.69 billion.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-debt_investment_19-2"><a href="#cite_note-debt_investment-19">[19]</a></sup> Between 1989 and 2013, foreign investment increased from NZ$9.7 billion to NZ$101.4 billion - a change of over 1,000%.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-scoop.co.nz_181-0"><a href="#cite_note-scoop.co.nz-181">[179]</a></sup> Between 1989 and 2007, foreign ownership of the New Zealand sharemarket went from 19% to 41% but has since dropped back to 33%. <sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (March 2023)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>In 2014, around 7% of all agriculturally productive land in New Zealand was foreign-owned.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-SALE_37-2"><a href="#cite_note-SALE-37">[37]</a></sup> In 2011, economist Bill Rosenberg claimed that the figure was closer to 9% when including foreign ownership of forestry land.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-182"><a href="#cite_note-182">[180]</a></sup> In March 2013, the financial sector, which includes the "big-four" Australian-owned banks, was worth NZ$39.3 billion - the largest share of the NZ$101.4 billion of foreign ownership of New Zealand companies at the time.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-scoop.co.nz_181-1"><a href="#cite_note-scoop.co.nz-181">[179]</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Impact">Impact</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=39" title="Edit section: Impact"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Between 1997 and 2014, foreign investors made NZ$50.3 billion profit, 68% of which went overseas. The <a href="/wiki/Campaign_Against_Foreign_Control_of_Aotearoa" title="Campaign Against Foreign Control of Aotearoa">Campaign Against Foreign Control of Aotearoa</a> (CAFCA) says this has a negative impact on the economy, arguing that when foreign investors buy up New Zealand companies, they tend to cut staff and push down wages.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-SALE_37-3"><a href="#cite_note-SALE-37">[37]</a></sup> It is also argued that growing foreign ownership has done nothing to reduce New Zealand's foreign debt. In 1984, private and public foreign debt was NZ$16 billion (NZ$50 billion in March 2013 dollars), which was less than half New Zealand's GDP at the time. By March 2013, total foreign debt stood at NZ$251 billion, well over 100% of New Zealand's GDP.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-scoop.co.nz_181-2"><a href="#cite_note-scoop.co.nz-181">[179]</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Data">Data</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Economy_of_New_Zealand&amp;action=edit&amp;section=40" title="Edit section: Data"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>

<dd><i>New Zealand dollars (NZ$) per US$1</i> – 1.4771 (2016), 1.2652 (2012), 1.3869 (2005), 1.5248 (2004), 1.9071 (2003), 2.1622 (2002), 2.3788 (2001), 2.2012 (2000), 1.8886 (1999), 1.8632 (1998), 1.5083 (1997), 1.4543 (1996), 1.5235 (1995)</dd></dl>

Based on this chart, several key points can be observed.

Significant fluctuations: Immigration data (including arrivals, departures and net numbers) show significant year-to-year fluctuations. This may reflect the impact of policy changes, changes in the international environment or economic conditions on migration flows.

Notable changes in 2020: The 2020 data show a significant decline followed by a rapid rebound. This pattern may be related to the global COVID-19 pandemic, with travel restrictions and lockdowns in 2020 likely leading to a temporary decline in immigration numbers.

Changes in net migration:

  • Before 2020, net migration showed a steady upward trend.
  • In 2021 and 2022, net migration will be negative, indicating that more people left than arrived during these two years. This may be related to border policies and economic recovery after the epidemic.
  • Net migration rose sharply in 2023, reaching a recent high, which may reflect a significant recovery in migration activity as the global epidemic situation improves and borders reopen.

Difference between median and quartiles:

  • China, the Philippines, and India have relatively high median distributions, indicating that these countries have large numbers of immigrants relative to other countries.
  • The data distribution for Japan, Canada, and the United States is relatively low, which may indicate relatively low numbers of immigrants from these countries.

Presence of outliers:

  • The outliers in the boxplot (the small dots in the plot) appear primarily in the data for China, the Philippines, and the United States, indicating that there were years when immigration from these countries was unusually high or low.

Data dispersion:

  • The higher boxes for the Philippines and China indicate greater variability in the data for these countries, i.e. greater fluctuations in the number of immigrants.
  • In contrast, countries such as Canada, the United States, Germany and the United Kingdom have smaller boxes, indicating that their data distribution is more concentrated and the number of immigrants is relatively stable.

[Analysis]¶

This correlation matrix provides correlation coefficients between various economic indicators and immigration data in the data set, which can be used to reveal the degree of association between variables. Here is an analysis of some key points in the correlation matrix:

Correlation of GDP per capita with other indicators:

  • There is a high positive correlation (0.8636) with Government debt in GDP (%), indicating that GDP per capita growth is usually accompanied by an increase in the government debt ratio.
  • There is a moderate positive correlation (0.4669) with the inflation rate (%), which may imply that when the economy performs well, the price level also rises.
  • The correlation with Unemployment (%) is lower (0.417817) but still positive, which may reflect that economic growth does not always immediately solve employment problems.

Correlation between immigration data (Arrivals, Departures, Net) and economic indicators:

  • Net migration (Net) is negatively correlated with the government debt ratio (-0.262693), possibly indicating that years with higher government debt do not necessarily attract more net migration.
  • Departures have a strong negative correlation with the inflation rate (-0.863678), suggesting that more people may choose to leave when inflation is higher.
  • The negative correlation between arrivals and the inflation rate is also very significant (-0.725276), suggesting that inflation may affect the decision to immigrate.

Correlation between inflation rate and unemployment rate:

  • There is a slight negative correlation between the inflation rate and the unemployment rate (-0.079779), a finding that is contrary to the traditional Phillips curve and may require further data exploration and background understanding.

[Analysis]¶

From the correlation matrix of the combined data, the following conclusions can be observed about the correlation between immigration country data and GDP, unemployment rate, and inflation rate:

GDP and immigration countries:

  • New Zealand's GDP is positively correlated with immigration flows from various countries, especially those with large immigration flows, such as China and India. This may indicate an increase in immigration from these countries as New Zealand's economy grows and opportunities within the country increase.
  • This positive correlation may be indicative of the attractiveness of the New Zealand economy, especially for people in countries with rapidly developing economies who may seek better living and work opportunities.

Unemployment rate and immigration countries:

  • The lack of significant correlation between the unemployment rate and immigration flows may indicate that fluctuations in the unemployment rate are relatively independent of the effects of immigration, or that changes in the unemployment rate are driven by broader domestic economic factors.

Inflation rates and immigration countries:

  • The negative correlation between inflation rates and immigration flows may indicate that New Zealand may have been less attractive to immigrants during periods of higher inflation, as high inflation is often associated with rising costs of living and economic instability.

Taken together, from the correlation between immigrants' nationality of origin and New Zealand's economic indicators, it can be seen that countries with good and stable economic conditions are more able to attract immigrants, especially from countries with active economies and large populations. This analysis can provide data support for New Zealand's immigration policy and economic development strategy, helping policymakers better understand the interaction between immigration and the national economy.

Conclusion¶

This data analysis reveals the complex links between New Zealand's GDP, inflation, unemployment and immigration flows. First, we find a significant positive relationship between New Zealand's GDP growth and government debt. This suggests that in years when the economy performs well, the government may stimulate the economy by increasing investment and expanding fiscal spending, which in turn increases debt levels. This situation reminds policymakers that while promoting economic growth, they also need to pay attention to the sustainability of debt. Especially when economic growth slows down, high debt may pose a threat to financial stability.

At the same time, this study also observed a negative correlation between the inflation rate and immigrant inflows and outflows, revealing that high inflation may weaken New Zealand's attractiveness and push people to look for a more stable economic environment. In addition, the analysis found that although inflation and unemployment show a slight negative correlation, this is contrary to the traditional Phillips Curve and may imply that current economic policies or global economic conditions have changed the applicability of this classic economic model.

In terms of immigration data, especially net migration, there is a negative correlation with government debt, reflecting that in years of high debt, New Zealand may become less attractive to immigrants. In addition, the high degree of correlation between immigration flows, especially the strong correlation between departure and entry, highlights the complexity of immigration decisions being affected by multiple factors, which requires policymakers to further analyze specific factors to optimize immigration policy and economic development. strategy.

Taken together, these correlations between New Zealand's economic indicators and immigration data reveal how economic performance, government policy and global economic conditions combine to influence the country's attractiveness and population movement patterns. These findings provide data support for the development of more forward-looking and responsive economic and immigration policies, helping policymakers better understand the interaction between the economy and immigration.

Key findings:¶

  1. Economic performance and government debt:
    There is a high positive correlation between New Zealand's GDP per capita and government debt, suggesting that when the economy is performing well, government debt levels may increase due to expanded investment and fiscal spending. This trend requires policymakers to remain vigilant in debt management to prevent fiscal risks if the economy slows down.

  2. Inflation, unemployment and immigration flows:
    Inflation rates are negatively correlated with migrant arrivals and departures, suggesting that high inflation may drive outflows and make New Zealand less attractive. In addition, the slight negative correlation between inflation and unemployment is contrary to the traditional Phillips curve, and further exploration of the economic mechanism behind this unconventional relationship is needed.

  3. Immigration and government debt:
    The negative correlation between immigration data (particularly net migration) and government debt may indicate that New Zealand becomes less attractive to immigrants during periods of higher debt. This may be related to economic uncertainty or fiscal austerity measures, affecting the inflow and outflow of migrants.

  4. Economic impact of immigration:
    The correlation between migration data and various economic indicators (especially GDP, inflation and unemployment) highlights the complex interaction between migration and macroeconomic factors. The analysis shows that when the economy is doing well, it attracts more immigrants, while hard times can hinder the inflow.
